window.extraSections = {
  featured: [
    { id: 'f1', name: 'Brihadeeswarar Temple', location: 'Thanjavur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva', image: 'images/featured/brihadeeswarar.jpg', summary: 'Great Living Chola Temple and UNESCO site.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.7828, lng: 79.1318, sthalaVaralaru: 'Built by Raja Raja Chola I in 1010 CE, the Brihadeeswarar Temple stands as one of the greatest achievements of Chola architecture. The vimana (tower) rises to 216 feet and is topped by an 80-ton single granite capstone. Legend says the stone was moved to the top using a 6-km long ramp. The temple was the first in the world to be built entirely of granite. The Nandi (bull) at the entrance, carved from a single rock, weighs 25 tons. Raja Raja Chola I dedicated this temple to Lord Shiva, naming the deity Rajarajeswarar. It was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987 as part of the Great Living Chola Temples.' },
    { id: 'f2', name: 'Meenakshi Amman Temple', location: 'Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Meenakshi & Sundareswarar', image: 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/royalatr1973/rajarajan/main/tamil-temples/images/featured/meenakshi.jpg?v=2', summary: 'Iconic Madurai complex with towering gopurams.', timings: 'Morning: 5:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:30 PM', lat: 9.9195, lng: 78.1193, sthalaVaralaru: 'According to legend, the Pandya king Malayadhwaja Pandya and his wife Kanchanamala performed a yajna seeking a son. Instead, a three-year-old girl with three breasts emerged from the holy fire. A divine voice told the king to name her Thadaathagai and raise her as a prince. When she met Lord Shiva on Mount Kailash, her third breast disappeared, fulfilling the prophecy that she would marry the man before whom this happened. Lord Shiva came to Madurai as Sundareswarar and married Meenakshi. The temple complex covers 14 acres with 14 gopurams, the tallest being the southern tower at 170 feet.' },
    { id: 'f3', name: 'Ramanathaswamy Temple', location: 'Rameswaram', district: 'Ramanathapuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva', image: 'images/featured/rameswaram.jpg', summary: 'Pilgrimage center known for long corridors.', timings: 'Morning: 5:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 9.2881, lng: 79.3174, sthalaVaralaru: 'Lord Rama, after defeating Ravana in Lanka, wished to atone for the sin of killing a Brahmin. He sent Hanuman to bring a Shiva Lingam from Kailash. When Hanuman was delayed, Sita made a small lingam from sand so that the auspicious time would not pass. Hanuman arrived with the Kailash lingam, and Rama installed both. The temple has the longest corridor of any Hindu temple in India, stretching 1,220 meters. There are 22 sacred wells (theerthams) within the temple, each believed to have curative properties.' },
    { id: 'f4', name: 'Nataraja Temple', location: 'Chidambaram', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Lord Nataraja (Shiva)', image: 'images/featured/nataraja.jpg', summary: 'Cosmic dance hall of Lord Shiva — the Chidambaram Rahasyam.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 11.3992, lng: 79.6935, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Nataraja Temple at Chidambaram is one of the five Pancha Sabhai (cosmic dance halls) and represents the Akasha (space/ether) element among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. The temple enshrines Lord Shiva in the Nataraja form — performing the Ananda Tandava (cosmic dance of bliss). The Chidambaram Rahasyam (secret) is a curtain behind the deity that, when opened, reveals empty space adorned with golden vilva leaves, symbolizing the formless nature of the divine. The temple is unique as it is managed by Dikshithars, a community of Vedic Brahmins who trace their lineage to the sages who first witnessed Nataraja\'s dance. The temple covers 40 acres with four massive gopurams decorated with 108 dance poses from the Natya Shastra.' },
    { id: 'f5', name: 'Ranganathaswamy Temple', location: 'Srirangam, Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Lord Ranganatha (Vishnu)', image: 'images/featured/srirangam.jpg', summary: 'Largest functioning Hindu temple in the world.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:15 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.8627, lng: 78.6873, sthalaVaralaru: 'Sri Ranganathaswamy Temple at Srirangam is the foremost among the 108 Divya Desams and the largest functioning Hindu temple complex in the world. Spread over 156 acres, it has 7 concentric prakarams (enclosure walls) and 21 gopurams. The reclining form of Lord Ranganatha (Vishnu) here is one of the most sacred images in Vaishnavism. The temple was the headquarters of the Sri Vaishnava movement, where Ramanuja spent much of his life teaching. The annual 21-day Vaikunta Ekadasi festival draws over a million pilgrims. The temple\'s Rajagopuram, completed in 1987, is one of the tallest in Asia at 236 feet.' },
    { id: 'f6', name: 'Kapaleeshwarar Temple', location: 'Mylapore, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Lord Shiva', image: 'images/featured/kapaleeshwarar.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Shiva temple in the heart of Chennai.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0339, lng: 80.2696, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kapaleeshwarar Temple in Mylapore is one of the most important Shiva temples in Chennai, mentioned in the Thevaram hymns of the Nayanmars. The name Kapaleeshwarar refers to Lord Shiva who wears the skull (kapala). According to legend, Goddess Parvati worshipped Shiva here in the form of a peacock — hence the name Mylapore (Mayil = peacock, Pore = place). The original temple was on the seashore and was destroyed during Portuguese colonial rule. The current temple, built in the Dravidian style by the Vijayanagara kings in the 16th century, features a towering gopuram and is the cultural heart of Mylapore, one of Chennai\'s oldest neighborhoods.' },
    { id: 'f7', name: 'Thiruvannamalai Arunachaleswarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvannamalai', district: 'Thiruvannamalai', deity: 'Lord Arunachaleswarar (Shiva)', image: 'images/featured/thiruvannamalai.jpg', summary: 'Fire element temple at the foot of the sacred Arunachala hill.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 3:30 PM - 9:30 PM', lat: 12.2310, lng: 79.0685, sthalaVaralaru: 'Arunachaleswarar Temple represents the Agni (Fire) element among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. The Arunachala hill itself is worshipped as a manifestation of Shiva, making it unique among all Shiva temples. When Vishnu and Brahma quarreled about who was supreme, Shiva appeared as an infinite column of fire that neither could find the end of — this column became the Arunachala hill. The temple covers 25 acres and has four massive gopurams. The Karthigai Deepam festival, when a huge flame is lit atop Arunachala hill visible for miles, draws millions of devotees. The Girivalam (circumambulation of the hill), a 14-km path, is performed by lakhs of devotees on every full moon night. Ramana Maharshi\'s ashram at the hill\'s base makes this a major spiritual center.' },
    { id: 'f8', name: 'Sarangapani Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Vishnu', image: 'images/featured/sarangapani.jpg', summary: 'One of the most important Divya Desam temples in Kumbakonam.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.9617, lng: 79.3770, sthalaVaralaru: 'Sarangapani Temple is the largest Vishnu temple in Kumbakonam and one of the most important among the 108 Divya Desams. The 12-tier rajagopuram (173 feet) is one of the tallest in South India. According to legend, Lord Vishnu appeared here to bless Hema Rishi. The name Sarangapani means "one who holds the Saranga bow." The temple\'s sanctum is built in the shape of a chariot, and the idol of Sarangapani is in a standing posture. This temple was greatly patronized by the Chola, Nayak, and Vijayanagara dynasties. It is one of three major temples in Kumbakonam that every pilgrim visits.' },
    { id: 'f9', name: 'Suchindram Thanumalayan Temple', location: 'Suchindram', district: 'Kanyakumari', deity: 'Thanumalayan (Brahma-Vishnu-Shiva)', image: 'images/featured/suchindram.jpg', summary: 'Unique temple dedicated to the Hindu Trinity.', timings: 'Morning: 4:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 5:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 8.1541, lng: 77.4651, sthalaVaralaru: 'Suchindram Thanumalayan Temple is unique in Hinduism as it houses the Trinity — Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva — in a single lingam called Sthanu-Mal-Ayan (Sthanu = Shiva, Mal = Vishnu, Ayan = Brahma). According to legend, Sage Atri\'s wife Anasuya was famous for her chastity. The wives of the Trinity tested her by sending their husbands in disguise. Anasuya turned them into babies, and when the crisis was resolved, the three gods merged into one form here. The temple features musical pillars in the Alankara Mandapam — hitting each pillar produces a different musical note. The 18-foot Hanuman statue and the massive Nandi are other notable features. Near Kanyakumari, it is a major pilgrimage destination.' },
    { id: 'f10', name: 'Thyagaraja Temple', location: 'Tiruvarur', district: 'Tiruvarur', deity: 'Lord Thyagaraja (Shiva)', image: 'images/featured/tiruvarur.jpg', summary: 'Temple with the largest temple chariot in India.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.7706, lng: 79.6345, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Thyagaraja Temple at Tiruvarur is one of the Pancha Sabhai (cosmic dance halls) and houses the famous Ajapa Natana form of Shiva\'s dance. The temple tank Kamalalayam (Lotus Tank) is one of the largest in Tamil Nadu. The temple chariot (Ther) is the largest in India. According to legend, this is the birthplace of the great Carnatic music trinity composer Thyagaraja. The temple was praised by all four of the Saivite Nayanmars who composed the Thevaram. The Chola kings lavished patronage upon this temple, making it one of the wealthiest in the region. The annual Thyagaraja Aradhana music festival draws classical musicians from across the world.' },
    { id: 'f11', name: 'Nellaiappar Temple', location: 'Tirunelveli', district: 'Tirunelveli', deity: 'Lord Nellaiappar (Shiva)', image: 'images/featured/nellaiappar.jpg', summary: 'Twin temple complex with musical pillars and chain mandapam.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 8.7270, lng: 77.6920, sthalaVaralaru: 'Nellaiappar Temple is the Thamira Sabhai (Copper Hall) among the Pancha Sabhai, where Lord Shiva performed the cosmic dance. The twin temples of Nellaiappar (Shiva) and Kanthimathi Amman (Parvati) are connected by a chain mandapam with stone chains carved from a single rock — a marvel of Dravidian architecture. The musical pillars in the Mani Mandapam produce the Saptaswaram (seven musical notes) when tapped. According to legend, a merchant\'s daughter offered nellu (paddy) to the poor, and Shiva blessed the city — hence "Nellai." The Sangili Mandapam connecting both temples was built by the Nayak kings. The temple is one of the 276 Paadal Petra Sthalams.' },
    { id: 'f12', name: 'Ekambareswarar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Earth Lingam)', image: 'images/featured/ekambareswarar.jpg', summary: 'Earth element Pancha Bhootha temple with a 3,500-year-old mango tree.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.8520, lng: 79.7006, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ekambareswarar Temple represents Prithvi (Earth) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams and is one of the largest temples in India, covering 25 acres. The Prithvi Lingam was made of sand by Goddess Parvati under a mango tree as penance. The sacred mango tree (Ekamra Natha = Lord of the Mango Tree) is believed to be 3,500 years old, with four branches representing the four Vedas, each yielding mangoes of different tastes. The 11-tier rajagopuram stands 59 meters tall, making it one of the tallest in South India. The temple has 1,000 pillars in its mandapam and was greatly expanded by the Chola and Vijayanagara kings. Kanchipuram, known as the City of Thousand Temples, considers this as its most important Shiva shrine.' }
  ],
  navagraha: [
    { id: 'n1', name: 'Suryanar Kovil', location: 'Suryanar Kovil, Aduthurai', district: 'Mayiladuthurai', deity: 'Surya (Sun)', image: 'images/navagraha/1.jpg', summary: 'Dedicated Surya sthalam in the Navagraha circuit.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.0012, lng: 79.4040, sthalaVaralaru: 'This is the only temple in India where all nine planetary deities (Navagrahas) are enshrined, with Surya (Sun God) as the presiding deity. According to legend, Sage Kalava was afflicted by leprosy caused by the combined curse of the Navagrahas. He prayed intensely to Surya, who appeared and cured him. Grateful, the sage established this temple. The Sun God here faces east and is depicted with his two consorts, Usha and Pratyusha, riding a chariot driven by seven horses. The temple was built during the Chola period. Devotees visit to seek relief from the malefic effects of the Sun (Surya dosha) in their horoscope, especially for issues related to authority, health, and vitality.' },
    { id: 'n2', name: 'Thingalur Kailasanathar Temple', location: 'Thingalur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Chandra (Moon)', image: 'images/navagraha/2.jpg', summary: 'Moon-associated sthalam in the Navagraha route.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9854, lng: 79.4455, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thingalur is the sthalam for Chandra (Moon God). According to Puranic legend, Chandra married the 27 daughters of Daksha (representing the 27 nakshatras) but showed excessive affection towards Rohini, neglecting the others. Angered, Daksha cursed Chandra to lose his brilliance. Chandra came here and worshipped Lord Shiva, who placed him on his head (hence Chandrasekhar) and granted that the moon would wax and wane in a monthly cycle rather than losing his light entirely. The presiding deity is Lord Kailasanathar (Shiva). Devotees visit to mitigate adverse effects of a weak Moon, which governs mind, emotions, and mental peace.' },
    { id: 'n3', name: 'Vaitheeswaran Koil', location: 'Vaitheeswaran Koil', district: 'Mayiladuthurai', deity: 'Angaraka / Sevvai (Mars)', image: 'images/navagraha/3.jpg', summary: 'Mars (Sevvai) sthalam; also famed as divine healer temple.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 11.2340, lng: 79.6640, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vaitheeswaran Koil is the sthalam for Angaraka (Mars/Sevvai). Lord Shiva here is worshipped as Vaitheeswaran (Divine Physician) who cured diseases of the Devas after the churning of the ocean. Mars (Angaraka) was born from Shiva\'s sweat drop that fell on the earth. He was afflicted with leprosy and came here to worship Shiva, who cured him. The temple tank "Siddhamirtham" is believed to have curative properties; devotees bathe in it for healing. The temple is also world-famous for Nadi Jothidam (palm leaf astrology), where one\'s past, present, and future are believed to be written on ancient palm leaves by Sage Agastya.' },
    { id: 'n4', name: 'Swetharanyeswarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvenkadu', district: 'Mayiladuthurai', deity: 'Budhan (Mercury)', image: 'images/navagraha/4.jpg', summary: 'Mercury (Budhan) sthalam with rich sthala puranam.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.2507, lng: 79.7417, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvenkadu is the sthalam for Budhan (Mercury). The name means "White Forest" (Swetha Aranyam) as Lord Shiva appeared here in a forest of white-barked trees. Budhan (Mercury), the son of Chandra and Tara, worshipped Shiva here to gain wisdom and eloquence. The presiding deity Swetharanyeswarar (Shiva) is self-manifested. The temple has a separate shrine for Budhan. Worshipping here is believed to improve intelligence, communication skills, business acumen, and academic excellence. Budhan governs education, speech, and analytical abilities in Vedic astrology.' },
    { id: 'n5', name: 'Apatsahayeswarar Temple', location: 'Alangudi', district: 'Thiruvarur', deity: 'Guru / Brihaspati (Jupiter)', image: 'images/navagraha/5.jpg', summary: 'Jupiter (Guru) sthalam in Kumbakonam belt.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.6680, lng: 79.4010, sthalaVaralaru: 'Alangudi is the sthalam for Guru/Brihaspati (Jupiter), the preceptor of the Devas. Lord Shiva here is Apatsahayeswarar - the one who helps in times of distress. According to legend, when the Devas were defeated by Asuras, Brihaspati prayed to Shiva here for help. Shiva granted him the power to guide and protect the Devas. Jupiter governs wisdom, fortune, children, spirituality, and higher learning. Devotees visit during Guru peyarchi (Jupiter transit) to seek blessings for prosperity, progeny, and spiritual growth. The temple is in the Kumbakonam-Thiruvarur belt, surrounded by paddy fields.' },
    { id: 'n6', name: 'Agneeswarar Temple', location: 'Kanjanur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Sukran (Venus)', image: 'images/navagraha/6.jpg', summary: 'Venus (Sukran) sthalam near Suryanar Kovil.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9894, lng: 79.3969, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kanjanur is the sthalam for Sukran (Venus), the preceptor of the Asuras. Lord Agni (Fire God) worshipped Shiva here, hence the deity is called Agneeswarar. Sukran once lost his eye when he was kicked by Lord Vishnu during the Vamana avatar. He came to Kanjanur and worshipped Shiva, who restored his vision. Venus governs love, marriage, luxury, beauty, arts, and material comforts. Worshipping here is believed to bring prosperity, remove obstacles in marriage, and bestow artistic talents. The temple also has shrines for all Navagrahas.' },
    { id: 'n7', name: 'Dharbaranyeswarar Temple', location: 'Thirunallar', district: 'Karaikal (Puducherry)', deity: 'Sani (Saturn)', image: 'images/navagraha/7.jpg', summary: 'Saturn (Sani) sthalam, one of the most visited Navagraha temples.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.8433, lng: 79.8131, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirunallar is the sthalam for Sani (Saturn), the most feared yet most worshipped Navagraha. The famous legend of King Nala illustrates Saturn\'s power: despite being a righteous king, Nala suffered immensely during his Sani Dasha (Saturn period), losing his kingdom, wealth, and even his wife Damayanti. He came to Thirunallar and bathed in the sacred tank called "Nala Theertham." Lord Shiva (Dharbaranyeswarar) relieved him from Saturn\'s affliction. This is the most visited Navagraha temple. Devotees flock here especially during Sani peyarchi (Saturn transit) and on Saturdays. Bathing in Nala Theertham is believed to reduce the severity of Sani Dasha.' },
    { id: 'n8', name: 'Naganathaswamy Temple', location: 'Thirunageswaram', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Rahu', image: 'images/navagraha/8.jpg', summary: 'Rahu sthalam known for milk abhishekam phenomenon.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9428, lng: 79.3146, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirunageswaram is the sthalam for Rahu, the shadow planet (ascending lunar node). The temple is famous for the miraculous "Rahu Kala Pooja" - during Rahu Kalam (the inauspicious period of Rahu each day), milk offered to the Rahu idol is said to change color, turning blue. This phenomenon draws thousands of devotees. According to legend, the serpent Adisesha worshipped Shiva here, hence the name Naganathaswamy (Lord of Serpents). Rahu dosha can cause unexpected troubles, fear, and confusion. Worshipping here with milk abhishekam is believed to neutralize Rahu\'s malefic effects and bring clarity of mind.' },
    { id: 'n9', name: 'Naganathar Temple', location: 'Keezhaperumpallam', district: 'Mayiladuthurai', deity: 'Ketu', image: 'images/navagraha/9.jpg', summary: 'Ketu sthalam completing the Navagraha nine.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 11.2690, lng: 79.7550, sthalaVaralaru: 'Keezhaperumpallam is the sthalam for Ketu, the shadow planet (descending lunar node). Ketu is the body of the demon Swarbhanu, whose head became Rahu after Lord Vishnu severed it with the Sudarshana Chakra during the distribution of amrit. Ketu came to this sacred place and worshipped Lord Shiva to attain salvation and divine status. The presiding deity is Naganathar (Shiva). Ketu governs moksha (liberation), spiritual inclination, and sudden events. Worshipping here is believed to remove Ketu dosha, which can cause mysterious ailments, spiritual confusion, and unexpected life changes. This temple completes the Navagraha circuit.' }
  ],
  panchabhootha: [
    { id: 'p1', name: 'Ekambareswarar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Prithvi Lingam (Earth)', image: 'images/panchabhootha/1.jpg', summary: 'Earth element (Prithvi Lingam) among Pancha Bhootha temples.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.8520, lng: 79.7006, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ekambareswarar Temple represents Prithvi (Earth) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. According to legend, Goddess Parvati once playfully covered Lord Shiva\'s eyes, plunging the world into darkness. As penance, she came to Kanchipuram and made a Shiva Lingam out of sand (earth) under a mango tree on the banks of the Vegavathi river. Lord Shiva tested her devotion by sending fire and flood, but Parvati embraced the lingam tightly, leaving her marks on it. The Prithvi Lingam here still bears these marks. The temple covers 25 acres with a towering 11-tier rajagopuram (59 meters). The sacred mango tree is believed to be 3,500 years old, with four branches representing the four Vedas, each yielding differently flavored fruits.' },
    { id: 'p2', name: 'Jambukeswarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvanaikaval, Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Appu Lingam (Water)', image: 'images/panchabhootha/2.jpg', summary: 'Water element (Appu Lingam) temple near Srirangam.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.8535, lng: 78.7066, sthalaVaralaru: 'Jambukeswarar Temple represents Appu (Water) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. The legend tells of a spider (Sri) and an elephant (Yanai) who were both devotees of Shiva. The spider wove webs over the lingam as a canopy to protect it from falling leaves, while the elephant poured water to clean it, destroying the webs. This conflict led to their repeated battles across births. The Shiva Lingam here is always partially submerged in water from an underground spring that has never dried up, representing the water element. The presiding Goddess, Akilandeswari, is one of the most powerful forms of the Goddess. Adi Shankaracharya tamed her fierce energy by installing Sri Chakra earrings on her.' },
    { id: 'p3', name: 'Arunachaleswarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvannamalai', district: 'Thiruvannamalai', deity: 'Agni Lingam (Fire)', image: 'images/panchabhootha/3.jpg', summary: 'Fire element (Agni Lingam), famed for Karthigai Deepam.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 3:30 PM - 9:30 PM', lat: 12.2317, lng: 79.0670, sthalaVaralaru: 'Arunachaleswarar Temple represents Agni (Fire) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. When Brahma and Vishnu argued about who was superior, Shiva appeared as an infinite column of fire (Jyotirlinga) and challenged them to find its top or bottom. Brahma flew upward as a swan and Vishnu dug downward as a boar; neither could find the end. Shiva then manifested as Arunachala hill, considered the oldest hill on earth. The annual Karthigai Deepam festival features a massive flame lit on the hilltop, visible for miles. The Girivalam (circumambulation) path around Arunachala hill is 14 km long and is walked by millions. Ramana Maharshi attained enlightenment here and his ashram sits at the base of the hill.' },
    { id: 'p4', name: 'Srikalahasteeswara Temple', location: 'Srikalahasti', district: 'Tirupati (Andhra Pradesh)', deity: 'Vayu Lingam (Air)', image: 'images/panchabhootha/4.jpg', summary: 'Air element (Vayu Lingam), ancient Shaivite shrine.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 2:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.7497, lng: 79.6981, sthalaVaralaru: 'Srikalahasteeswara Temple represents Vayu (Air) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. The temple gets its name from three devoted animals: Sri (spider), Kala (serpent), and Hasti (elephant), who worshipped Shiva here. The spider wove a web shelter over the lingam, the serpent placed a gem on it, and the elephant bathed it with water. The inner sanctum lamp flickers constantly despite no wind, proving the presence of the air element. This is the only Pancha Bhootha temple outside Tamil Nadu, located on the banks of the Swarnamukhi river. It is also called "Dakshina Kasi" (Kashi of the South). The Rahu-Ketu dosha nivarana pooja here is famous across South India.' },
    { id: 'p5', name: 'Thillai Natarajar Temple', location: 'Chidambaram', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Akasha Lingam (Space/Ether)', image: 'images/panchabhootha/5.jpg', summary: 'Space element (Akasha Lingam) at Chidambaram.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 10:00 PM', lat: 11.3994, lng: 79.6937, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thillai Natarajar Temple represents Akasha (Space/Ether) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams. This is the only temple where Shiva is worshipped in his Natarajar (Cosmic Dancer) form as the main deity. The Chidambara Rahasyam (Secret of Chidambaram) is a curtain in the sanctum behind which there is empty space decorated with golden vilva leaves - representing the formless nature of God (Akasha). Lord Shiva performed the Ananda Tandavam (Dance of Bliss) here, defeating the demon Muyalakan (symbolizing ignorance). The temple is managed by Dikshitars, a hereditary community of priests. The Arudra Darshan festival draws hundreds of thousands. The temple architecture encodes many cosmic principles including the golden ratio.' }
  ],
  vinayagar: [
    { id: 'v1', name: 'Ucchi Pillayar Temple (Rockfort)', location: 'Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Ucchi Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/1.jpg', summary: 'Iconic Ganesha atop the Rockfort hill in Trichy, offering panoramic views of the city.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.8184, lng: 78.7092, sthalaVaralaru: 'Perched atop the ancient Rockfort (Malaikottai) in Trichy, this Vinayagar temple is reached by climbing 437 rock-cut steps. Legend says when Lord Vinayagar was carrying the Shiva Lingam given by Sage Vishwamitra, he set it down here and it could not be moved. The rock is believed to be one of the oldest in the world, dating back 3.8 billion years. The Pallava king Mahendravarman I carved the rock-cut cave temples here in the 7th century.' },
    { id: 'v2', name: 'Pillayarpatti Karpaga Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Pillayarpatti, near Karaikudi', district: 'Sivaganga', deity: 'Karpaga Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/2.jpg', summary: 'Ancient rock-cut cave temple with a magnificent Ganesha carved from natural rock.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.2350, lng: 78.7830, sthalaVaralaru: 'Pillayarpatti Karpaga Vinayagar is one of the most revered Ganesha temples in Tamil Nadu. The deity is carved directly from the rock face of a natural cave, dating back to the 7th century Pandya period. The idol is believed to be Swayambhu (self-manifested). The name Karpaga Vinayagar means the wish-fulfilling Ganesha. The Chettinad community considers this their presiding deity. The cave temple has beautiful Pandya-era inscriptions.' },
    { id: 'v3', name: 'Manakula Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Pondicherry', district: 'Puducherry', deity: 'Manakula Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/3.jpg', summary: 'Famous seaside Ganesha temple in the French Quarter of Pondicherry.', timings: 'Morning: 5:45 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:30 PM', lat: 11.9340, lng: 79.8360, sthalaVaralaru: 'Manakula Vinayagar Temple is over 500 years old, located near the Pondicherry beach in the French Quarter. The name comes from Manal (sand) and Kulam (pond) — Ganesha near the sand pond. During the French colonial period, the French attempted to destroy this temple multiple times, but each time the idol was mysteriously found intact. The temple elephant blesses devotees daily. During the Brahmotsavam, the deity is taken in a grand procession.' },
    { id: 'v4', name: 'Siddhivinayak Temple', location: 'Prabhadevi, Mumbai', district: 'Mumbai', deity: 'Siddhivinayak', image: 'images/vinayagar/4.jpg', summary: 'India\'s richest and most visited Ganesha temple in Mumbai.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 12:00 PM - 9:50 PM', lat: 19.0169, lng: 72.8310, sthalaVaralaru: 'Shree Siddhivinayak Temple was built in 1801 by Laxman Vithu and Deubai Patil. The deity has his trunk turned to the right (Siddhi Vinayak form), which is considered especially powerful and rare. The temple was originally a small structure but was rebuilt into the current grand form in 1990. It is one of the richest temples in India, visited by Bollywood stars and politicians. Tuesday is the most auspicious day to visit. The golden dome was added in 1990.' },
    { id: 'v5', name: 'Thiruvalanchuzhi Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Thiruvalanchuzhi, near Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Swetha Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/5.jpg', summary: 'Birthplace of saint Sambandhar; white Ganesha on the banks of Cauvery.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9530, lng: 79.4280, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvalanchuzhi is the birthplace of Thirugnana Sambandhar, one of the 63 Nayanmars. The Vinayagar here is Swetha (white) Vinayagar, unique because the idol is white in color. The name means the place where the river (Cauvery) goes around (valanchuzhi = whirlpool). The temple is on the banks of the Cauvery where the river makes a natural curve. Pilgrims visiting Kumbakonam Navagraha temples traditionally begin here.' },
    { id: 'v6', name: 'Thirupparankundram Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Thirupparankundram, Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Vinayagar (Rock-cut)', image: 'images/vinayagar/6.jpg', summary: 'One of the six abodes of Murugan with an ancient rock-cut Ganesha shrine.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:30 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 9.8788, lng: 78.0700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirupparankundram is primarily known as the first Arupadaiveedu of Lord Murugan, but it also houses a magnificent ancient Vinayagar shrine. The rock-cut cave temple dates to the 8th century Pandya period. The Ganesha here is carved directly from the hill rock. This temple complex is a rare example where Shiva, Vishnu, Murugan, and Vinayagar are all worshipped in the same rock-cut cave. It is one of the Jain-Hindu composite temples of Tamil Nadu.' },
    { id: 'v7', name: 'Ashtadasabhuja Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Tiruchenkode, Namakkal', district: 'Namakkal', deity: 'Ashtadasabhuja Vinayagar (18-armed)', image: 'images/vinayagar/7.jpg', summary: 'Rare 18-armed Ganesha deity atop the Tiruchengode hill.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.3830, lng: 77.8930, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Tiruchengode hilltop temple houses a rare Ashtadasabhuja (18-armed) Vinayagar, one of the most unique Ganesha forms in India. Each arm holds a different weapon or attribute. The hill temple is also famous for the Arthanareeswara (half-male, half-female) form of Lord Shiva. The temple is reached by climbing 1,200 steps or by road. The 18-armed form represents Vinayagar\'s supreme cosmic power over all directions.' },
    { id: 'v8', name: 'Selva Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Thiruvaiyaru', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Selva Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/8.jpg', summary: 'Ganesha temple in the town where saint Thyagaraja composed his masterpieces.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.8830, lng: 79.1030, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvaiyaru is famous as the town where the great Carnatic music composer Thyagaraja lived and composed. The Selva Vinayagar Temple here is ancient, dating to the Chola period. Selva means wealth — this Ganesha bestows prosperity. The temple is on the banks of the Cauvery river. Every January, the Thyagaraja Aradhana music festival brings thousands of musicians here, and they traditionally pay respects at this Vinayagar temple before performing.' },
    { id: 'v9', name: 'Vellai Pillaiyar Temple', location: 'Mylapore, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Vellai Pillaiyar (White Ganesha)', image: 'images/vinayagar/9.jpg', summary: 'White-stone Ganesha in the cultural heart of Chennai, near Kapaleeshwarar Temple.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0340, lng: 80.2700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vellai (white) Pillaiyar Temple sits in the heart of Mylapore, Chennai\'s oldest cultural neighborhood. The deity is made of white stone and is considered self-manifested. The temple is adjacent to the famous Kapaleeshwarar Temple. Mylapore has been a center of Tamil culture for over 2,000 years — the area is mentioned in Sangam literature. The temple is especially crowded during Vinayagar Chaturthi and every Wednesday.' },
    { id: 'v10', name: 'Thirunaageswaram Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Thirunageswaram, Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Nagathamman Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/10.jpg', summary: 'Vinayagar shrine within the famous Rahu temple complex at Thirunageswaram.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9428, lng: 79.3146, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirunageswaram is most famous as the Rahu sthalam in the Navagraha circuit, but its Vinayagar shrine is equally revered. Devotees traditionally worship Vinayagar first before proceeding to the Rahu shrine. The Ganesha here is believed to remove Sarpa Dosha (serpent affliction) along with Rahu dosha. The temple has Chola-period inscriptions and is part of the Kumbakonam temple belt.' },
    { id: 'v11', name: 'Saatchi Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Saatchi Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/11.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Ganesha temple in the temple town of Kumbakonam.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9603, lng: 79.3770, sthalaVaralaru: 'Saatchi Vinayagar Temple is one of the most ancient Ganesha temples in Kumbakonam. The deity is known as Saatchi (witness) Vinayagar — the Ganesha who witnesses and blesses all ceremonies. Traditionally, weddings and auspicious functions in the Kumbakonam region begin with prayers at this temple. The temple has beautiful Chola-era architecture and is located in the heart of the town.' },
    { id: 'v12', name: 'Karupar Swami Temple (Karuppanasamy)', location: 'Ayyarpadi, near Tirunelveli', district: 'Tirunelveli', deity: 'Vinayagar with Karuppar', image: 'images/vinayagar/12.jpg', summary: 'Unique temple combining Vinayagar and guardian deity Karuppar worship.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 8.6500, lng: 77.7300, sthalaVaralaru: 'This unique temple in the Tirunelveli region combines the worship of Vinayagar with the powerful guardian deity Karuppar. In the southern Tamil Nadu tradition, Vinayagar is worshipped alongside village guardian deities. The temple represents the folk religion tradition of Tamil Nadu where Sanskritic deities merge with local village guardians. The annual festival features elaborate rituals unique to the southern Tamil tradition.' },
    { id: 'v13', name: 'Kanipakam Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Kanipakam, Chittoor', district: 'Chittoor (AP)', deity: 'Varasiddhi Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/13.jpg', summary: 'Self-growing Ganesha idol that continues to increase in size over centuries.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 2:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.4350, lng: 79.0150, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kanipakam Vinayagar is one of the most miraculous Ganesha temples in South India. The deity was originally a small self-manifested idol found by three disabled men in a well. As they prayed, each was cured. Over the centuries, the idol has been continuously growing in size — what was once a small idol is now over 3 feet tall. The well water around the idol is considered sacred. During Vinayagar Chaturthi, over a million devotees visit. The temple was built by Chola king Kulottunga I in the 11th century.' },
    { id: 'v14', name: 'Madhur Maha Ganapathi Temple', location: 'Madhur, Kasaragod', district: 'Kasaragod (Kerala)', deity: 'Maha Ganapathi', image: 'images/vinayagar/14.jpg', summary: 'Kerala\'s most famous Ganesha temple on the banks of Madhuvahini river.', timings: 'Morning: 5:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:30 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.4470, lng: 75.0230, sthalaVaralaru: 'Madhur Maha Ganapathi Temple on the banks of the Madhuvahini river is one of Kerala\'s oldest and most revered Ganesha temples. The idol is believed to have been installed by Parashurama. The temple is famous for its annual Madhur Ganapathi festival. The architecture is classic Kerala style with copper-clad roof. The presiding deity is depicted in a unique seated posture. Historical records mention this temple from the 10th century.' },
    { id: 'v15', name: 'Thenupuriswarar Temple Vinayagar', location: 'Patteeswarar, Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Patteeswarar Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/15.jpg', summary: 'Magnificent Chola-era Vinayagar in one of the largest Shiva temples of the region.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9300, lng: 79.2800, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Vinayagar shrine within the massive Thenupuriswarar (Patteeswarar) Temple complex is one of the finest Chola-era Ganesha sculptures. The main temple is one of the largest Shiva temples in the Kumbakonam region, covering over 10 acres. The Vinayagar here is worshipped first before entering the main Shiva shrine, following the tradition of Prathamapuja (first worship). The temple has inscriptions from Rajaraja Chola I and Rajendra Chola I.' },
    { id: 'v16', name: 'Aathmanatha Swami Temple Vinayagar', location: 'Avudaiyar Kovil', district: 'Pudukkottai', deity: 'Vinayagar (with Lingam)', image: 'images/vinayagar/16.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Vinayagar shrine within the Athmanathar temple known for its cosmic Lingam.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.3670, lng: 78.7970, sthalaVaralaru: 'Avudaiyar Kovil is famous for the Athmanathar temple where the Shiva Lingam rests on a Yoni that is shaped like the sacred syllable Om when viewed from above. The Vinayagar shrine here is ancient and pilgrims must worship here before viewing the main sanctum. The temple dates to the early Chola period and has Pandya-era inscriptions. The Om-shaped Avudaiyar (base) is considered an architectural marvel.' },
    { id: 'v17', name: 'Siddhi Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Thalaivasal, near Attur', district: 'Salem', deity: 'Siddhi Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/17.jpg', summary: 'Popular Ganesha temple in the Salem region known for wish fulfilment.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.5900, lng: 78.6400, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thalaivasal Siddhi Vinayagar Temple is one of the most popular Ganesha temples in the Salem region. Siddhi means accomplishment — devotees believe prayers here bring success in all endeavors. The temple is especially crowded during exam seasons when students seek Vinayagar\'s blessings. The annual Vinayagar Chaturthi festival features elaborate decorations and a procession through the town.' },
    { id: 'v18', name: 'Thiru Palani Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Tiruchendur', district: 'Thoothukudi', deity: 'Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/18.jpg', summary: 'Vinayagar shrine within the famous Tiruchendur Subrahmanya Temple complex.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 8.4975, lng: 78.1190, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Vinayagar shrine within the Tiruchendur Subrahmanya (Murugan) Temple is significant because Lord Ganesha is worshipped here as the elder brother of Murugan. According to legend, Ganesha blessed Murugan before his battle with the demon Surapadman on the shores of Tiruchendur. The seaside temple complex is one of the most visited in Tamil Nadu. The Vinayagar here faces the sea, blessing devotees before they enter the Murugan sanctum.' },
    { id: 'v19', name: 'Valampuri Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Thiruvaiyaru road, Thanjavur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Valampuri Vinayagar (Right-trunk)', image: 'images/vinayagar/19.jpg', summary: 'Rare right-trunk Ganesha considered extremely auspicious and powerful.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.8200, lng: 79.1200, sthalaVaralaru: 'Valampuri (right-trunk) Vinayagar is one of the rarest and most auspicious forms of Ganesha. While most Ganesha idols have the trunk turning to the left, the right-trunk form (Valampuri) is considered extremely powerful and demanding strict ritual worship. This temple near Thanjavur houses one such rare deity. Devotees believe that worshipping Valampuri Vinayagar brings swift results but requires sincere devotion. The temple attracts scholars and spiritual seekers.' },
    { id: 'v20', name: 'Ranjangudi Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Ranjangudi, near Sivaganga', district: 'Sivaganga', deity: 'Ranjangudi Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/20.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Ganesha temple with Nayak-era architecture in the Chettinad region.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.2960, lng: 78.8870, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ranjangudi Vinayagar Temple is one of the prominent Ganesha temples in the Chettinad-Sivaganga region. The temple has Nayak-era architecture with beautiful gopurams and mandapams. The Ganesha here is known for solving disputes and bringing harmony — the name Ranjan means one who pleases. The temple was patronized by the Sivaganga Zamindar family. The annual Chaturthi festival draws devotees from across the district.' },
    { id: 'v21', name: 'Eachanari Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Eachanari, Coimbatore', district: 'Coimbatore', deity: 'Eachanari Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/21.jpg', summary: 'One of the most famous Ganesha temples in western Tamil Nadu near Coimbatore.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.9340, lng: 76.9250, sthalaVaralaru: 'Eachanari Vinayagar Temple near Coimbatore is one of the most revered Ganesha temples in western Tamil Nadu. The deity is in a unique standing posture. The temple was built during the Chera period and renovated by the Nayak kings. It is especially popular during Vinayagar Chaturthi when elaborate processions and special abhishekams are conducted.' },
    { id: 'v22', name: 'Varasiddhi Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Varasiddhi Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/22.jpg', summary: 'One of the Ashta Vinayaka temples in the sacred temple city of Kanchipuram.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8340, lng: 79.7030, sthalaVaralaru: 'Varasiddhi Vinayagar Temple in Kanchipuram is one of the Ashta Vinayaka (eight Ganesha) temples of the sacred city. Varasiddhi means the Ganesha who grants boons and accomplishments. This Vinayagar temple is traditionally visited before entering the major temples of the city. The temple has Pallava-era foundations with later Chola additions.' },
    { id: 'v23', name: 'Pullabootham Ganesha Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Pullabootha Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/23.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Ganesha temple in Kanchipuram known for wish-fulfilment.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8380, lng: 79.7080, sthalaVaralaru: 'Pullabootham Ganesha Temple in Kanchipuram houses a unique form of Vinayagar worshipped for the removal of obstacles. Pullabootha refers to the form associated with sacred grass (dharba). The temple is part of the rich Ganesha worship tradition of Kanchipuram.' },
    { id: 'v24', name: 'Arulmigu Vinayagar Temple', location: 'Porur, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Arulmigu Vinayagar', image: 'images/vinayagar/24.jpg', summary: 'Popular Ganesha temple in Chennai known for Wednesday and Chaturthi worship.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0350, lng: 80.1580, sthalaVaralaru: 'Arulmigu Vinayagar Temple in Porur, Chennai, is a popular neighborhood Ganesha temple. The temple sees huge crowds on Wednesdays and during Vinayagar Chaturthi. Porur was historically a village with the famous Porur lake and the temple has been the spiritual center of the community for centuries.' },
    { id: 'v25', name: 'Mahaganapathy Temple', location: 'Tiruvidaimarudur, Thanjavur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Maha Ganapathy', image: 'images/vinayagar/25.jpg', summary: 'One of the Ashta Vinayaka temples in the Cauvery delta sacred belt.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9950, lng: 79.4530, sthalaVaralaru: 'Mahaganapathy Temple at Tiruvidaimarudur in the Cauvery delta is one of the Ashta Vinayaka temples. The deity is Maha Ganapathy in a grand, powerful form. The Ganesha here is worshipped before visiting the main Shiva temple (Mahalinga Swamy). The temple has inscriptions from Rajaraja Chola I.' }
  ],
  murugan: [
    { id: 'm1', name: 'Thirupparankundram Murugan Temple', location: 'Thirupparankundram, Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Subramanyar (1st Arupadaiveedu)', image: 'images/murugan/1.jpg', summary: 'First of the six Arupadaiveedu; where Murugan married Devasena.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:30 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 9.8788, lng: 78.0700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirupparankundram is the first Arupadaiveedu (six battle camps of Lord Murugan). After vanquishing the demon Surapadman, Lord Murugan married Devasena (Indra\'s daughter) here. The temple is carved into a massive rock hill and is one of the oldest rock-cut temples in South India, dating to the 8th century. The rock-cut shrine houses deities of Shiva, Vishnu, Ganesha, and Durga alongside Murugan — a rare composite temple. The annual Thaipusam festival is celebrated grandly here.' },
    { id: 'm2', name: 'Tiruchendur Murugan Temple', location: 'Tiruchendur', district: 'Thoothukudi', deity: 'Senthilandavar (2nd Arupadaiveedu)', image: 'images/murugan/2.jpg', summary: 'Second Arupadaiveedu; seaside temple where Murugan defeated Surapadman.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 8.4975, lng: 78.1190, sthalaVaralaru: 'Tiruchendur is the second Arupadaiveedu, the only one on the seashore. This is where Lord Murugan fought and defeated the demon Surapadman in an epic battle on the shores of the Bay of Bengal. The demon was split into two — one half became a peacock (Murugan\'s vahana) and the other a rooster (his flag emblem). The temple is built on a rocky promontory overlooking the sea. The Skanda Sashti festival in October-November reenacts the 6-day war with dramatic performances.' },
    { id: 'm3', name: 'Palani Dhandayuthapani Temple', location: 'Palani', district: 'Dindigul', deity: 'Dhandayuthapani (3rd Arupadaiveedu)', image: 'images/murugan/3.jpg', summary: 'Third Arupadaiveedu; Murugan as the renunciate ascetic atop Palani Hill.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.4386, lng: 77.5200, sthalaVaralaru: 'Palani is the third Arupadaiveedu. When Sage Narada gave a divine fruit to Shiva, he said it should go to whoever circles the universe first. Murugan flew on his peacock, but Ganesha simply circumambulated his parents (who represent the universe). Feeling wronged, young Murugan renounced everything and came to Palani as a mendicant with just a staff (danda) and loincloth. The deity is made of Navapashana (nine poisons/minerals) by Siddhar Bogar. The idol has medicinal properties — the abhishekam milk is said to be curative.' },
    { id: 'm4', name: 'Swamimalai Murugan Temple', location: 'Swamimalai, near Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Swaminathan (4th Arupadaiveedu)', image: 'images/murugan/4.jpg', summary: 'Fourth Arupadaiveedu; where Murugan taught the meaning of Om to his own father Shiva.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9570, lng: 79.2270, sthalaVaralaru: 'Swamimalai is the fourth Arupadaiveedu. Here, the child Murugan taught the meaning of Pranava (Om) to his own father Lord Shiva, hence earning the name Swaminatha (the Lord who became Guru to his father). The temple sits atop a small hill reached by 60 steps representing the 60 Tamil years. The Chola-era bronze casting tradition of Swamimalai is world-famous — the artisans here still use the ancient lost-wax technique to create temple bronzes.' },
    { id: 'm5', name: 'Thiruthani Murugan Temple', location: 'Thiruthani', district: 'Tiruvallur', deity: 'Murugan (5th Arupadaiveedu)', image: 'images/murugan/5.jpg', summary: 'Fifth Arupadaiveedu; where Murugan rested after the war and married Valli.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.1750, lng: 79.6120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruthani is the fifth Arupadaiveedu. After the cosmic war with Surapadman, Lord Murugan came to this hill to rest (thani = solitude/peace). This is also where he married Valli, the tribal girl he wooed with the help of his brother Ganesha. The temple sits atop a hill reached by 365 steps (one for each day). It is one of the most visited Murugan temples near Chennai. Devotees perform Girivalam (circumambulation) of the hill during Karthigai.' },
    { id: 'm6', name: 'Pazhamudhircholai Murugan Temple', location: 'Alagar Hills, Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Murugan (6th Arupadaiveedu)', image: 'images/murugan/6.jpg', summary: 'Sixth Arupadaiveedu; Murugan in a sacred grove atop the Alagar Hills.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 6:00 PM', lat: 10.0800, lng: 78.0880, sthalaVaralaru: 'Pazhamudhircholai is the sixth and final Arupadaiveedu, located atop the Alagar Hills (Solaimalai) near Madurai. The name means "grove of ripened fruits." Poet Avvaiyar, thinking she knew everything, was humbled by young Murugan here when he asked her a philosophical question about a fruit. The temple is set amid dense forests and has a waterfall called Noopura Gangai. Unusually, Murugan is worshipped here with both his consorts Valli and Devasena.' },
    { id: 'm7', name: 'Marudhamalai Murugan Temple', location: 'Marudhamalai, Coimbatore', district: 'Coimbatore', deity: 'Dhandayuthapani', image: 'images/murugan/7.jpg', summary: 'Hilltop Murugan temple in the Western Ghats near Coimbatore.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.0440, lng: 76.8940, sthalaVaralaru: 'Marudhamalai Temple sits on a hill in the Western Ghats foothills near Coimbatore. The name comes from Marudha (a type of medicinal tree) and Malai (hill). Lord Murugan appeared here to cure a sage of illness using the medicinal herbs from the hill. The temple has Chera-period origins and was rebuilt during the Nayak period. The surrounding forest is rich in medicinal plants. The annual Thaipusam festival features kavadi processions up the hill.' },
    { id: 'm8', name: 'Sikkal Singaravelan Temple', location: 'Sikkal, near Nagapattinam', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Singaravelan', image: 'images/murugan/8.jpg', summary: 'Temple where Murugan first performed the cosmic Vel dance.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.8020, lng: 79.7260, sthalaVaralaru: 'Sikkal Singaravelan Temple is famous for the Singaravelar (Beautiful Lord) form of Murugan. This is where the first ever Kavadi was believed to have been performed. The saint Idumban carried two hills on a kavadi (pole) as offering to Murugan. The Vaikasi Visakam festival here is legendary — the chariot is one of the tallest temple chariots in Tamil Nadu. The Shanmuga dance performed here is believed to be the origin of the Kavadi tradition practiced worldwide.' },
    { id: 'm9', name: 'Kundrakudi Murugan Temple', location: 'Kundrakudi, near Karaikudi', district: 'Sivaganga', deity: 'Shanmugar', image: 'images/murugan/9.jpg', summary: 'Hilltop Murugan temple in the Chettinad region with panoramic views.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.1680, lng: 78.8030, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kundrakudi (hill village) Shanmugar Temple sits atop a small hill in the Chettinad region. The deity Shanmugar (six-faced) is revered by the wealthy Nattukottai Chettiar community. The temple was rebuilt and expanded by the Chettiars who made their fortune in Southeast Asia. The hilltop offers panoramic views of the Chettinad countryside. A large golden Vel (spear) was installed by devotees. The Kanda Sashti festival is celebrated with great fervor.' },
    { id: 'm10', name: 'Thiruchendur Subrahmanya Temple', location: 'Valliyoor, Tirunelveli', district: 'Tirunelveli', deity: 'Subrahmanyar with Valli', image: 'images/murugan/10.jpg', summary: 'Temple where Murugan wooed and married the tribal princess Valli.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 8.3820, lng: 77.6010, sthalaVaralaru: 'Valliyoor is where Lord Murugan came in disguise to woo the beautiful tribal girl Valli. He first came as an old man, then as a young hunter. When she rejected him, he asked Ganesha to appear as a wild elephant to frighten her into his arms. Valli finally recognized his divinity and married him. This Valli Thirumanam (wedding) is celebrated grandly every year. The temple is set amidst the beautiful foothills near Tirunelveli.' },
    { id: 'm11', name: 'Ettukudi Murugan Temple', location: 'Ettukudi, near Mayiladuthurai', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Subramanyar', image: 'images/murugan/11.jpg', summary: 'Scenic Murugan temple on a small hill near the coast.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.1200, lng: 79.7400, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ettukudi means "Murugan\'s abode on eight hills." The temple sits on a small hillock near the coast between Sirkazhi and Mayiladuthurai. Lord Murugan appeared here in a forest clearing to bless a group of sages performing penance. The temple has a unique octagonal design reflecting the eight hills. The annual Panguni Uthiram festival features a grand procession.' },
    { id: 'm12', name: 'Viralimalai Murugan Temple', location: 'Viralimalai, near Pudukkottai', district: 'Pudukkottai', deity: 'Murugar with Peacock', image: 'images/murugan/12.jpg', summary: 'Temple on the Hill of Peacocks where wild peacocks roam freely.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.5980, lng: 78.5460, sthalaVaralaru: 'Viralimalai (Hill of Fingers/Spread) is famous for the hundreds of wild peacocks that roam freely around the temple. Since the peacock is Murugan\'s vahana (vehicle), this is considered an extremely sacred site. The temple sits atop a hill reached by steps. The sight of peacocks dancing during monsoon is considered a divine blessing. The temple was patronized by the Pudukkottai Thondaiman kings. The annual Thaipusam and Panguni Uthiram festivals draw large crowds.' },
    { id: 'm13', name: 'Thiruporur Murugan Temple', location: 'Thiruporur, near Chennai', district: 'Chengalpattu', deity: 'Kandaswami', image: 'images/murugan/13.jpg', summary: 'Major Murugan temple near Chennai; associated with Murugan\'s war march.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.7230, lng: 80.1870, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruporur (sacred war town) is where Lord Murugan halted during his war march against the demons. The name comes from "Thiru Por Ur" — sacred battle town. The temple sits on a hillock reached by a short climb. This is one of the most visited Murugan temples near Chennai. The Skanda Sashti and Thaipusam festivals feature elaborate kavadi processions. The temple was rebuilt during the Pallava and later Vijayanagar periods.' },
    { id: 'm14', name: 'Kandha Kottam', location: 'George Town, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Kandaswami', image: 'images/murugan/14.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Murugan temple in the heart of Chennai\'s commercial district.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0950, lng: 80.2830, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kandha Kottam (Fort of Kanda/Murugan) is one of the oldest temples in Chennai, located in the bustling George Town area. The temple has been here since the pre-colonial era and survived the British development of Madras. The deity Kandaswami is worshipped by the trading community of George Town. The annual Thaipusam festival procession through the streets of George Town is one of Chennai\'s oldest religious traditions.' },
    { id: 'm15', name: 'Vayalur Murugan Temple', location: 'Vayalur, near Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Murugan with Valli and Devasena', image: 'images/murugan/15.jpg', summary: 'Murugan temple near Trichy with both consorts; a Sangam-era site.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9100, lng: 78.7700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vayalur Murugan Temple near Trichy is mentioned in Sangam literature (over 2,000 years old). Lord Murugan is worshipped here with both consorts Valli and Devasena. The temple is surrounded by agricultural fields (Vayal = paddy field). The poet Nakkeerar composed verses about this temple. The Thaipusam and Panguni Uthiram festivals are celebrated with traditional rituals preserved from the Sangam era.' },
    { id: 'm16', name: 'Thirumuruganpoondi Temple', location: 'Thirumuruganpoondi, near Thanjavur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Murugan', image: 'images/murugan/16.jpg', summary: 'Murugan temple established where the Lord appeared from an anthill.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.8660, lng: 79.2060, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirumuruganpoondi is where Lord Murugan is said to have appeared from an anthill (Putru/Poondi). The temple sits near the banks of a river in the Thanjavur region. The deity emerged spontaneously from the earth, making it a Swayambhu (self-manifested) shrine. The surrounding area has rich Chola-period heritage. The temple is part of the larger network of Murugan temples in the Cauvery delta region.' },
    { id: 'm17', name: 'Kumarakottam Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Kumara (Murugan)', image: 'images/murugan/17.jpg', summary: 'One of the oldest Murugan temples, inside the sacred city of Kanchipuram.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8350, lng: 79.7000, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kumarakottam in Kanchipuram is one of the oldest Murugan temples in Tamil Nadu. Kumara (young prince) is another name for Murugan. The temple is believed to have been established during the Pallava period. Kanchipuram, one of India\'s seven sacred cities, houses temples for all major deities, and this Murugan shrine holds a special place in the city\'s spiritual geography. The temple has ancient inscriptions from the Pallava and Chola periods.' },
    { id: 'm18', name: 'Senganur Murugan Temple', location: 'Senganur, near Karur', district: 'Karur', deity: 'Murugan', image: 'images/murugan/18.jpg', summary: 'Murugan temple on the banks of river Amaravathi with ancient Chera history.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9400, lng: 78.0600, sthalaVaralaru: 'Senganur Murugan Temple is set on the banks of the river Amaravathi near Karur, the ancient Chera capital. The temple has roots in the Sangam period when Murugan worship was the predominant religion of the Tamil land. The area is rich in Chera dynasty heritage. The deity is worshipped with traditional Sangam-era rituals. The annual Karthigai festival features the lighting of hill-top fires visible across the Amaravathi valley.' },
    { id: 'm19', name: 'Thiruverkadu Murugan Temple', location: 'Thiruverkadu, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Murugan with Vel', image: 'images/murugan/19.jpg', summary: 'Murugan temple adjacent to the famous Karumariamman shrine at Thiruverkadu.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0670, lng: 80.1120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruverkadu Murugan Temple sits alongside the famous Karumariamman Temple. The Murugan shrine here is known for its powerful Vel (divine spear). The area name Thiruverkadu means "sacred neem forest" — both temples sit in what was once a dense neem grove. Devotees visiting the Amman temple traditionally also worship Murugan here. The Thaipusam and Skanda Sashti festivals are celebrated with processions connecting both temples.' },
    { id: 'm20', name: 'Pazhanisamy Temple', location: 'Kodaikanal', district: 'Dindigul', deity: 'Pazhanisamy (Murugan)', image: 'images/murugan/20.jpg', summary: 'Murugan temple in the hill station of Kodaikanal amidst misty mountains.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.2380, lng: 77.4890, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Pazhanisamy (Lord of Palani) Temple in Kodaikanal is set at over 2,000 meters altitude in the misty Western Ghats. While the main Palani temple is the Arupadaiveedu, this hilltop shrine near Kodaikanal extends Murugan\'s presence into the cloud forests. The temple is surrounded by eucalyptus and shola forests. The cool mountain air and the spiritual atmosphere make this a unique pilgrimage experience combining nature and devotion.' },
    { id: 'm21', name: 'Vadapalani Murugan Temple', location: 'Vadapalani, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Vel Murugan', image: 'images/murugan/21.jpg', summary: 'One of the most popular Murugan temples in Chennai, in the heart of the city.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0520, lng: 80.2120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vadapalani Murugan Temple is one of the most visited temples in Chennai, located in the bustling Vadapalani area. The temple was built in 1890 by Annasamy Nayagar. Lord Murugan is worshipped with his Vel (divine spear). The temple gave its name to the entire neighborhood which is now also famous for the Tamil film industry studios nearby. The annual Thaipusam and Panguni Uthiram festivals feature kavadi processions through the streets.' },
    { id: 'm22', name: 'Skandagiri Murugan Temple', location: 'Skandagiri, Salem', district: 'Salem', deity: 'Skandagiri Murugan', image: 'images/murugan/22.jpg', summary: 'Hilltop Murugan temple in the Salem region with panoramic views of the Eastern Ghats.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 11.6370, lng: 78.2100, sthalaVaralaru: 'Skandagiri (Murugan\'s hill) near Salem is a hilltop temple set amidst the Eastern Ghats. Lord Murugan is worshipped here as the commander of the divine army. The hill offers sweeping views of the surrounding valleys and Salem city. The temple has ancient origins dating to the Chola period and was expanded during the Vijayanagar era. The Karthigai Deepam festival when the hilltop is illuminated with thousands of lamps is spectacular.' },
    { id: 'm23', name: 'Malaikovil Murugan Temple', location: 'Malaikovil, Tiruvannamalai', district: 'Tiruvannamalai', deity: 'Murugan', image: 'images/murugan/23.jpg', summary: 'Ancient hill temple of Murugan in the Tiruvannamalai region.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.3120, lng: 79.1450, sthalaVaralaru: 'Malaikovil (hill temple) near Tiruvannamalai is one of the lesser-known but ancient Murugan shrines in the region dominated by the great Arunachaleswarar Temple. The hilltop setting provides views of the Tiruvannamalai landscape. The temple has stone inscriptions from the Pallava and Chola periods. Local tradition holds that Murugan rested here during his southern march against the demons.' },
    { id: 'm24', name: 'Kundrathur Murugan Temple', location: 'Kundrathur, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Murugan', image: 'images/murugan/24.jpg', summary: 'Hilltop Murugan temple on the outskirts of Chennai; one of the Saptha Sthanams.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.9940, lng: 80.0990, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kundrathur (hill town) Murugan Temple on the outskirts of Chennai sits on a small hillock and is one of the important Murugan temples in the Chennai metropolitan area. The name Kundru means hill. The temple has Pallava-era origins and was expanded during the Chola period. It is also counted among the Saptha Sthanams of Murugan in some traditions. The surrounding area was once dense forest.' },
    { id: 'm25', name: 'Thirumuruganpundi Murugan Temple', location: 'Thirumuruganpundi, Tiruchirappalli', district: 'Tiruchirappalli', deity: 'Murugan (Swayambhu)', image: 'images/murugan/25.jpg', summary: 'Self-manifested Murugan temple on the banks of the Cauvery near Trichy.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.8370, lng: 78.8210, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirumuruganpundi near Tiruchirappalli is where Lord Murugan manifested himself from the earth (Swayambhu). The temple sits on the banks of the Cauvery river. Ancient Chola inscriptions describe royal patronage of this shrine. Devotees visiting the famous temples of Trichy — Srirangam, Rockfort, and Thiruvanaikaval — often include this Murugan temple in their pilgrimage circuit.' }
  ],
  amman: [
    { id: 'a1', name: 'Meenakshi Amman Temple', location: 'Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Meenakshi (Parvati)', image: 'images/amman/1.jpg', summary: 'Iconic twin temple for Meenakshi and Sundareswarar with towering gopurams.', timings: 'Morning: 5:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:30 PM', lat: 9.9195, lng: 78.1193, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Pandya king Malayadhwaja Pandya and his wife Kanchanamala performed a yajna seeking a son. Instead, a three-year-old girl with three breasts emerged from the holy fire. A divine voice told the king to name her Thadaathagai and raise her as a prince. When she met Lord Shiva on Mount Kailash, her third breast disappeared, fulfilling the prophecy. Lord Shiva came to Madurai as Sundareswarar and married Meenakshi. The complex covers 14 acres with 14 gopurams, the tallest being the southern tower at 170 feet. The temple has over 33,000 sculptures.' },
    { id: 'a2', name: 'Kamakshi Amman Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Kamakshi (Tripura Sundari)', image: 'images/amman/2.jpg', summary: 'One of the 3 Shakti Peethas; seat of Adi Shankaracharya\'s Sri Chakra.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.8423, lng: 79.7125, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kamakshi Amman Temple is one of the three holiest Shakti Peethas (the others being Madurai Meenakshi and Varanasi Visalakshi). Goddess Kamakshi is worshipped in the form of Tripura Sundari, seated in Padmasana (lotus posture). Adi Shankaracharya installed the Sri Chakra here to pacify the fierce energy of the Goddess. She was initially Ugra (fierce), and Shankaracharya transformed her into Shanta (peaceful) Swaroopini. The temple is one of the 51 Shakti Peethas where parts of Goddess Sati\'s body fell. The annual Brahmotsavam in February-March is a grand 9-day festival.' },
    { id: 'a3', name: 'Mariamman Temple', location: 'Samayapuram, Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Mariamman', image: 'images/amman/3.jpg', summary: 'Most visited Amman temple in Tamil Nadu; famed for healing powers.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:30 PM', lat: 10.8930, lng: 78.7370, sthalaVaralaru: 'Samayapuram Mariamman Temple is the richest and most visited Amman temple in Tamil Nadu. Mariamman is the Goddess of rain and disease — worshipped for curing smallpox, chicken pox, and other ailments. Legend says Goddess Parvati took the form of Mariamman to destroy the demon Tirisiran. The deity is a self-manifested (Swayambhu) idol. Devotees offer lemon garlands and neem leaves. The temple receives more revenue than most temples in Tamil Nadu. During the Panguni and Aadi month festivals, millions of devotees visit. Neem water (marundhu neer) is distributed as sacred healing water.' },
    { id: 'a4', name: 'Akilandeswari Temple', location: 'Thiruvanaikaval, Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Akilandeswari (Parvati)', image: 'images/amman/4.jpg', summary: 'Powerful Devi shrine within the Jambukeswarar (Water) temple complex.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.8535, lng: 78.7066, sthalaVaralaru: 'Akilandeswari (Goddess of the entire universe) resides within the Jambukeswarar Temple, one of the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams (Water). The Goddess was once so fierce that even the Devas feared her. Adi Shankaracharya tamed her energy by installing Sri Chakra earrings (Thaatagam) on her, transforming her from Ugra (fierce) to Shanta (peaceful). The earrings are believed to have been crafted from the poison that emerged during Samudra Manthan. The temple has five enclosures and is surrounded by water from the Cauvery river.' },
    { id: 'a5', name: 'Kali Amman Temple', location: 'Karur (Karuvarai)', district: 'Karur', deity: 'Kali (Bhadrakali)', image: 'images/amman/5.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Bhadrakali temple on the banks of river Amaravathi.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9575, lng: 78.0729, sthalaVaralaru: 'Karur Bhadrakali Temple is one of the most ancient Kali temples in Tamil Nadu. The deity is Bhadrakali — the benevolent yet fierce form of Goddess Kali. According to legend, Goddess Parvati took the form of Bhadrakali to destroy the demon Daruka. The temple is on the banks of the river Amaravathi. Karur was the ancient capital of the Chera dynasty, and this temple has inscriptions dating back over 1,500 years. The annual Panguni festival features grand car processions.' },
    { id: 'a6', name: 'Angala Parameswari Temple', location: 'Melmalayanur', district: 'Viluppuram', deity: 'Angala Parameswari', image: 'images/amman/6.jpg', summary: 'Famed Shakti temple known for fire-walking and trance rituals.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.1420, lng: 79.6490, sthalaVaralaru: 'Melmalayanur Angala Parameswari Temple is one of the most powerful Shakti temples in Tamil Nadu, famous for dramatic fire-walking festivals and devotees entering trance states. The Goddess is a fierce form of Parvati who appeared to destroy evil. Devotees perform kavadi and alaku (hook-swinging) during the annual Panguni festival spanning 18 days. Thousands of devotees walk on burning coals barefoot as an offering. The temple is also associated with Siddha traditions and occult sciences.' },
    { id: 'a7', name: 'Karumariamman Temple', location: 'Thiruverkadu, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Karumariamman', image: 'images/amman/7.jpg', summary: 'Popular Amman temple near Chennai; twin deities Karumari and Peri Amman.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0670, lng: 80.1120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruverkadu Karumariamman Temple houses two powerful forms of the Goddess — Karumariamman (dark-complexioned Mariamman) and Peri Amman. The temple has ancient origins and was revitalized during the Chola period. It is one of the Shakti Peethas of the region. Fridays and Tuesdays are especially crowded. During the Tamil month of Aadi, special poojas and abhishekams draw huge crowds from Chennai. The temple also has a Devi Mahatmyam (Durga Saptashati) recitation tradition.' },
    { id: 'a8', name: 'Punnainallur Mariamman Temple', location: 'Punnainallur, Thanjavur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Mariamman', image: 'images/amman/8.jpg', summary: 'Major Mariamman temple near Thanjavur; one of the oldest Amman shrines.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.7410, lng: 79.1070, sthalaVaralaru: 'Punnainallur Mariamman Temple near Thanjavur is one of the oldest and most revered Mariamman temples. The Goddess is believed to be Swayambhu (self-manifested). According to legend, the idol was discovered under a Punnai tree (Calophyllum) by a Chola king who was guided in a dream. The temple was patronized by the Thanjavur Nayaks and Marathas. During the Chithirai festival, the Goddess is taken in a grand chariot procession. Devotees offer turmeric, neem, and kumkum. The temple is a major center for seeking cures from diseases.' },
    { id: 'a9', name: 'Periyapalayathamman Temple', location: 'Coimbatore', district: 'Coimbatore', deity: 'Periyapalayathamman (Shakti)', image: 'images/amman/9.jpg', summary: 'Presiding Amman of Coimbatore city; ancient Shakti shrine.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:30 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 11.0005, lng: 76.9620, sthalaVaralaru: 'Periyapalayathamman Temple is the presiding Amman temple of Coimbatore city. The Goddess is a benevolent form of Shakti who protects the city and its people. The temple has been a center of worship for centuries. During the annual Pongal and Navaratri festivals, elaborate decorations and special poojas are held. The Goddess is adorned with silk sarees and gold jewelry during festival days. The temple is located in the heart of the city and is visited daily by thousands.' },
    { id: 'a10', name: 'Kulothamman Temple (Pazhaiyarai)', location: 'Pazhaiyarai, near Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Kulothamman (Durga)', image: 'images/amman/10.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Chola capital Amman temple; rare Durga with Chola history.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9180, lng: 79.2440, sthalaVaralaru: 'Pazhaiyarai was the early capital of the Chola empire before it moved to Thanjavur. The Kulothamman Temple is the presiding Amman shrine of this historic town. The Goddess Kulothamman (a form of Durga) was the family deity (Kula Deivam) of the Chola dynasty. The temple has rare Chola-period sculptures and inscriptions. It is believed that the Chola kings sought her blessings before going into battle. The temple is surrounded by rice fields and retains a quiet, ancient atmosphere.' },
    { id: 'a11', name: 'Adhiparasakthi Temple', location: 'Melmaruvathur', district: 'Chengalpattu', deity: 'Adhiparasakthi', image: 'images/amman/11.jpg', summary: 'Major modern Shakti temple with massive following; founded by Bangaru Adigalar.', timings: 'Morning: 4:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 2:00 PM - 10:00 PM', lat: 12.3550, lng: 79.7080, sthalaVaralaru: 'Adhiparasakthi Temple at Melmaruvathur was established by His Holiness Bangaru Adigalar. Devotees wear green and perform Abishekam with their own hands — a unique practice. Fridays and full moon days draw lakhs of devotees. The temple runs extensive social service programs including free education and healthcare.' },
    { id: 'a12', name: 'Bannari Mariamman Temple', location: 'Bannari, Erode', district: 'Erode', deity: 'Bannari Mariamman', image: 'images/amman/12.jpg', summary: 'Famous hilltop Mariamman temple at the foothills of the Western Ghats.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.3140, lng: 77.0570, sthalaVaralaru: 'Bannari Mariamman Temple sits at the foothills of the Western Ghats near the Sathyamangalam wildlife corridor. The Goddess protects travelers passing through the treacherous mountain passes. The temple was patronized by the Mysore kings. The annual Pongal festival features a massive fire-walking ceremony.' },
    { id: 'a13', name: 'Thillai Kali Amman Temple', location: 'Chidambaram', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Thillai Kali', image: 'images/amman/13.jpg', summary: 'Fierce form of Kali at Chidambaram; connected to the cosmic dance legend.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 11.3940, lng: 79.6870, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thillai Kali Temple at Chidambaram is deeply connected to the Natarajar legend. Kali challenged Shiva to a dance competition. When Shiva raised his leg in the Urdhva Tandava, Kali could not replicate it and accepted defeat. She was asked to reside outside the main temple. The Thillai Kali shrine is thus just outside the Natarajar Temple compound.' },
    { id: 'a14', name: 'Mundakanni Amman Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Mundakanni Amman', image: 'images/amman/14.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Amman temple in Kanchipuram with Pallava-era origins.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8400, lng: 79.7060, sthalaVaralaru: 'Mundakanni Amman Temple in Kanchipuram is one of the oldest Amman temples in the temple city. The name refers to the three-eyed Goddess. The temple has Pallava-era foundations and was expanded during the Chola period. The Goddess is worshipped in a fierce protective form alongside the more famous Kamakshi Amman Temple.' },
    { id: 'a15', name: 'Vadivudai Amman Temple', location: 'Tiruchirappalli', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Vadivudai Amman', image: 'images/amman/15.jpg', summary: 'Beautiful Amman temple adjacent to the Rockfort in Trichy.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.8200, lng: 78.7100, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vadivudai (beautifully formed) Amman Temple is located adjacent to the famous Rockfort in Tiruchirappalli. The Goddess is a graceful, benevolent form of Parvati. The temple is an important stop for pilgrims visiting the Rockfort Ucchi Pillayar temple. The annual Panguni Uthiram festival features a procession through the streets of Trichy.' },
    { id: 'a16', name: 'Mahalakshmi Temple', location: 'Triplicane, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Mahalakshmi', image: 'images/amman/16.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Lakshmi temple in the heart of Chennai near Parthasarathy Temple.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 13.0470, lng: 80.2780, sthalaVaralaru: 'Mahalakshmi Temple in Triplicane (Thiruvallikeni) is one of the oldest temples dedicated to the Goddess of Wealth in Chennai. Located near the famous Parthasarathy Temple, it has been a center of Lakshmi worship for centuries. Friday worship is especially popular. During Navaratri, special Lakshmi poojas draw thousands of devotees.' },
    { id: 'a17', name: 'Karpagambal Amman (Kapaleeshwarar)', location: 'Mylapore, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Karpagambal (Parvati)', image: 'images/amman/17.jpg', summary: 'Devi shrine within the iconic Kapaleeshwarar Temple; heart of Mylapore.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0340, lng: 80.2690, sthalaVaralaru: 'Karpagambal (Wish-fulfilling Mother) is the Devi shrine within the famous Kapaleeshwarar Temple at Mylapore. According to legend, Parvati worshipped Shiva here in the form of a peacock (Myil in Tamil, hence Mylapore). The Arubathu Moovar festival during Panguni celebrates the 63 Nayanmars with a grand 10-day procession through Mylapore.' },
    { id: 'a18', name: 'Ashtalakshmi Temple', location: 'Besant Nagar, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Ashtalakshmi (Eight forms of Lakshmi)', image: 'images/amman/18.jpg', summary: 'Seaside temple dedicated to the eight forms of Goddess Lakshmi.', timings: 'Morning: 6:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.9990, lng: 80.2710, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ashtalakshmi Temple on the shore of Elliot\'s Beach in Besant Nagar is dedicated to the eight forms of Goddess Lakshmi. Built in 1976, the multi-level temple rises from the beach with stunning sea views. Each level houses a different form of Lakshmi. It is one of the most photographed temples in Chennai.' },
    { id: 'a19', name: 'Kalikambal Temple', location: 'George Town, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Kalikambal (Kali)', image: 'images/amman/19.jpg', summary: 'Historic Kali temple in Chennai moved from Fort St. George by the British.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 13.0930, lng: 80.2840, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kalikambal Temple in George Town is one of Chennai\'s most historic temples. Originally located inside Fort St. George, the British moved it to its current location in 1640 when they built the fort. Freedom fighters offered prayers here during the independence movement. The annual Navaratri festival with Golu (doll display) is famous.' },
    { id: 'a20', name: 'Kottai Mariamman Temple', location: 'Dindigul', district: 'Dindigul', deity: 'Kottai Mariamman', image: 'images/amman/20.jpg', summary: 'Mariamman temple within the historic Dindigul Fort with hilltop views.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.3640, lng: 77.9700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kottai (Fort) Mariamman Temple sits within the historic Dindigul Fort built by Madurai Nayak kings. The Goddess has been the protector of the fort and its garrison for centuries. The hilltop fort offers panoramic views of Dindigul city. The Nayak kings and later Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan all respected this temple.' },
    { id: 'a21', name: 'Santhana Mariamman Temple', location: 'Sendamangalam, Namakkal', district: 'Namakkal', deity: 'Santhana Mariamman', image: 'images/amman/21.jpg', summary: 'Mariamman temple famed for blessings of progeny (Santhana = offspring).', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 11.4370, lng: 78.2570, sthalaVaralaru: 'Santhana Mariamman Temple at Sendamangalam is famous for blessing childless couples with progeny. Devotees from across Tamil Nadu visit seeking the Goddess\'s blessing for children. Special poojas and votive offerings are made by couples. The annual Aadi festival features traditional rituals.' },
    { id: 'a22', name: 'Ponniyamman Temple', location: 'Erode', district: 'Erode', deity: 'Ponniyamman (Golden Mother)', image: 'images/amman/22.jpg', summary: 'Presiding Amman of Erode city on the banks of the Cauvery.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 11.3400, lng: 77.7260, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ponniyamman (Golden Mother) Temple is the presiding Amman of Erode city, situated on the banks of the Cauvery river. The Goddess appeared in golden form to bless the people of this region. During Navaratri, the temple is decorated with thousands of lights. Erode is also the birthplace of social reformer Periyar.' },
    { id: 'a23', name: 'Marundeeswarar Temple (Tripurasundari)', location: 'Tiruvanmiyur, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Tripurasundari', image: 'images/amman/23.jpg', summary: 'Ancient temple with medicinal deity; Amman shrine for Tripurasundari.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 12.9830, lng: 80.2580, sthalaVaralaru: 'Marundeeswarar Temple at Tiruvanmiyur is an ancient temple where Shiva is worshipped as the Lord of Medicine. The Amman shrine houses Tripurasundari — the beautiful Goddess of the three worlds. The temple was built by the Pallavas and expanded by the Cholas. The Tripurasundari shrine is especially popular during Navaratri.' },
    { id: 'a24', name: 'Periyapalayathamman Temple', location: 'Velachery, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Periyapalayathamman', image: 'images/amman/24.jpg', summary: 'Popular Amman temple in south Chennai with a large devotee following.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 12.9760, lng: 80.2180, sthalaVaralaru: 'Periyapalayathamman Temple in Velachery is one of the popular Amman temples in south Chennai. The Goddess is the guardian deity of the Velachery area. Friday and Tuesday worship is especially significant. The annual Aadi festival features special poojas and processions through the neighborhood.' },
    { id: 'a25', name: 'Kattu Muthaliamman Temple', location: 'Puzhal, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Kattu Muthaliamman', image: 'images/amman/25.jpg', summary: 'Village guardian Amman temple near Chennai with ancient folk traditions.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 13.1530, lng: 80.1830, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kattu Muthaliamman Temple at Puzhal preserves the ancient Tamil village guardian deity tradition. Kattu means forest and Muthaliyamman is the first (chief) Goddess. The annual Kodai (festival) features elaborate folk rituals, terukoothu performances, and traditional offerings. The temple is an important example of living folk Hinduism in Tamil Nadu.' }
  ],
  jyotirlinga: [
    { id: 'j1', name: 'Somnath Temple', location: 'Veraval, Gujarat', district: 'Gir Somnath', deity: 'Somnath (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/1.jpg', summary: 'First Jyotirlinga; destroyed and rebuilt 17 times, symbol of Indian resilience.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 9:30 PM', lat: 20.8880, lng: 70.4012, sthalaVaralaru: 'Somnath is the first among the 12 Jyotirlingas. The Moon God (Soma/Chandra) built this temple after being cursed by Daksha to lose his lustre. He bathed in the Sarasvati river and worshipped Shiva, who blessed him to wax and wane. The temple was destroyed by Mahmud of Ghazni in 1026 CE and rebuilt multiple times — a total of 17 destructions and reconstructions. The present temple was rebuilt in 1951 under the leadership of Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel. Located on the Arabian Sea coast, it stands as a symbol of India\'s civilizational resilience.' },
    { id: 'j2', name: 'Mallikarjuna Temple', location: 'Srisailam, Andhra Pradesh', district: 'Kurnool', deity: 'Mallikarjuna (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/2.jpg', summary: 'Second Jyotirlinga atop the Nallamala Hills; also a Shakti Peetha.', timings: 'Morning: 4:30 AM - 3:30 PM | Evening: 6:00 PM - 10:00 PM', lat: 16.0744, lng: 78.8686, sthalaVaralaru: 'Mallikarjuna at Srisailam is the second Jyotirlinga, situated atop the Nallamala Hills on the banks of the Krishna River. When Shiva and Parvati\'s sons Ganesha and Murugan competed to circle the world, Murugan felt slighted and went to Mount Krauncha. Shiva and Parvati followed him and settled here as Mallikarjuna and Bhramaramba. The temple is both a Jyotirlinga and one of the 18 Maha Shakti Peethas. The surrounding forest is the Srisailam Tiger Reserve.' },
    { id: 'j3', name: 'Mahakaleshwar Temple', location: 'Ujjain, Madhya Pradesh', district: 'Ujjain', deity: 'Mahakaleshwar (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/3.jpg', summary: 'Third Jyotirlinga; only south-facing (Dakshinamurti) Jyotirlinga. Famous Bhasma Aarti.', timings: 'Morning: 4:00 AM - 11:00 PM', lat: 23.1828, lng: 75.7682, sthalaVaralaru: 'Mahakaleshwar in Ujjain is the third Jyotirlinga and the only one that faces south (Dakshinamurti), making it immensely powerful for tantric worship. Lord Shiva as Mahakala (Lord of Time/Death) destroyed the demon Dushana who was tormenting the people of Ujjain. The famous Bhasma Aarti at 4 AM uses ash from funeral pyres — one of the most intense rituals in Hinduism. Ujjain is also one of the four sites for the Kumbh Mela, held every 12 years on the banks of the Shipra River.' },
    { id: 'j4', name: 'Omkareshwar Temple', location: 'Omkareshwar Island, Madhya Pradesh', district: 'Khandwa', deity: 'Omkareshwar (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/4.jpg', summary: 'Fourth Jyotirlinga on an Om-shaped island in the Narmada River.', timings: 'Morning: 5:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 22.2452, lng: 76.1510, sthalaVaralaru: 'Omkareshwar is the fourth Jyotirlinga, located on an island in the Narmada River that is naturally shaped like the sacred syllable Om when viewed from above. The Devas and Demons once competed in worshipping Shiva, and the Lord appeared here pleased by their devotion. Two temples exist — Omkareshwar on the island and Amareshwar (Mamaleshwar) on the south bank. Pilgrims do a parikrama (circumambulation) of the island. The Narmada here is considered as holy as the Ganges.' },
    { id: 'j5', name: 'Kedarnath Temple', location: 'Kedarnath, Uttarakhand', district: 'Rudraprayag', deity: 'Kedarnath (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/5.jpg', summary: 'Fifth Jyotirlinga at 3,583m in the Himalayas; open only 6 months a year.', timings: 'Morning: 4:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM (May-Nov only)', lat: 30.7352, lng: 79.0669, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kedarnath at 3,583 meters is the highest Jyotirlinga, nestled in the Garhwal Himalayas near the Mandakini river. After the Mahabharata war, the Pandavas sought Shiva\'s forgiveness for killing their kinsmen. Shiva avoided them by disguising as a bull and diving into the ground. His hump emerged here as Kedarnath, while other body parts appeared at four other sites (forming the Panch Kedar). The temple survives extreme conditions — it was miraculously shielded from the devastating 2013 floods by a boulder that split the debris flow. Open only May to November.' },
    { id: 'j6', name: 'Bhimashankar Temple', location: 'Pune District, Maharashtra', district: 'Pune', deity: 'Bhimashankar (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/6.jpg', summary: 'Sixth Jyotirlinga in the Sahyadri range; source of the Bhima River.', timings: 'Morning: 4:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 19.0720, lng: 73.5360, sthalaVaralaru: 'Bhimashankar in the Sahyadri (Western Ghats) range is the sixth Jyotirlinga. Tripurasura, a powerful demon, gained immense power and threatened the gods. Lord Shiva defeated him in a fierce battle and the sweat from his body formed the Bhima River. The temple is surrounded by dense forests that are a wildlife sanctuary, home to the Giant Indian Squirrel (Shekru). The Nagara-style architecture dates to the 13th century. The temple is at the source of the Bhima River, a major tributary of the Krishna.' },
    { id: 'j7', name: 'Kashi Vishwanath Temple', location: 'Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh', district: 'Varanasi', deity: 'Vishwanath (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/7.jpg', summary: 'Seventh Jyotirlinga in the holiest city; one of the most sacred Hindu temples.', timings: 'Morning: 2:30 AM - 11:00 PM', lat: 25.3109, lng: 83.0107, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kashi Vishwanath in Varanasi is the seventh and most revered Jyotirlinga. Varanasi (Kashi) is the oldest continuously inhabited city in the world and Shiva\'s own city. It is believed that dying in Kashi grants instant moksha (liberation). Shiva as Vishwanath (Lord of the Universe) has resided here since the beginning of creation. The original temple was destroyed multiple times; the present one was built by Ahilyabai Holkar of Indore in 1780. The gold plating on the dome was donated by Maharaja Ranjit Singh. The Kashi Vishwanath Corridor, completed in 2021, has transformed the temple precinct.' },
    { id: 'j8', name: 'Trimbakeshwar Temple', location: 'Trimbak, Nasik, Maharashtra', district: 'Nasik', deity: 'Trimbakeshwar (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/8.jpg', summary: 'Eighth Jyotirlinga; source of the Godavari River at Brahmagiri Hill.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 9:00 PM', lat: 19.9322, lng: 73.5300, sthalaVaralaru: 'Trimbakeshwar near Nasik is the eighth Jyotirlinga, located at the source of the Godavari River at the foot of Brahmagiri Hill. The lingam here is unique — it has three faces representing Brahma, Vishnu, and Shiva (Tri-ambaka = three-eyed). The lingam is naturally formed and is covered with a jeweled crown that is revealed only during special poojas. Sage Gautama brought the Godavari (Dakshina Ganga) to this place by praying to Shiva. The Nasik Kumbh Mela is associated with this temple.' },
    { id: 'j9', name: 'Vaidyanath Temple', location: 'Deoghar, Jharkhand', district: 'Deoghar', deity: 'Vaidyanath (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/9.jpg', summary: 'Ninth Jyotirlinga; Shiva as the Divine Physician who heals all ailments.', timings: 'Morning: 4:00 AM - 3:30 PM | Evening: 6:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 24.4920, lng: 86.6997, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vaidyanath (Baidyanath) in Deoghar is the ninth Jyotirlinga. Ravana, the demon king of Lanka, performed extreme penance to Shiva on Mount Kailash, even offering his ten heads one by one. Pleased, Shiva agreed to accompany him to Lanka. But through Vishnu\'s trickery, Ravana set the lingam down here and it became rooted to the ground. Shiva as Vaidyanath (Divine Doctor) heals all physical and spiritual ailments. The Shravani Mela in July-August attracts millions of Kanwariyas who carry Ganga water from Sultanganj.' },
    { id: 'j10', name: 'Nageshwar Temple', location: 'Near Dwarka, Gujarat', district: 'Devbhoomi Dwarka', deity: 'Nageshwar (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/10.jpg', summary: 'Tenth Jyotirlinga near Dwarka; Shiva who defeated the demon Daaruka.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 5:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 22.3320, lng: 68.9667, sthalaVaralaru: 'Nageshwar near Dwarka is the tenth Jyotirlinga. A devout Shiva bhakta named Supriya was captured by the demon Daaruka and imprisoned. Even in prison, Supriya continued chanting Om Namah Shivaya. When Daaruka tried to kill him, Shiva appeared in his Nageshwar form and destroyed the demon with the Pashupata weapon. The 25-meter tall statue of seated Shiva at the entrance is a modern landmark. The temple is near the coast, between Dwarka and the Bet Dwarka island.' },
    { id: 'j11', name: 'Ramanathaswamy Temple', location: 'Rameswaram, Tamil Nadu', district: 'Ramanathapuram', deity: 'Ramanathaswamy (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/11.jpg', summary: 'Eleventh Jyotirlinga; installed by Lord Rama before crossing to Lanka.', timings: 'Morning: 5:00 AM - 1:00 PM | Evening: 3:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 9.2881, lng: 79.3174, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ramanathaswamy in Rameswaram is the eleventh Jyotirlinga, the only one in Tamil Nadu. Lord Rama installed a Shiva Lingam here to atone for killing Ravana (a Brahmin). When Hanuman was delayed in bringing a lingam from Kailash, Sita made one from sand. Both lingams are worshipped — the sand lingam (Ramalingam) as the main deity. The temple has the longest corridor of any Hindu temple (1,220 meters). Its 22 sacred wells (theerthams) are believed to have healing properties. Rameswaram is one of the Char Dham.' },
    { id: 'j12', name: 'Grishneshwar Temple', location: 'Ellora, Maharashtra', district: 'Aurangabad', deity: 'Grishneshwar (Shiva)', image: 'images/jyotirlinga/12.jpg', summary: 'Twelfth Jyotirlinga near the Ellora Caves; last in the sacred circuit.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 9:00 PM', lat: 20.0263, lng: 75.1790, sthalaVaralaru: 'Grishneshwar near the UNESCO World Heritage Ellora Caves is the twelfth and final Jyotirlinga. A devout woman named Kusuma performed daily worship by immersing a lingam in a lake. Her jealous co-wife killed her son, but when Kusuma continued her worship unmoved, Shiva appeared, restored her son, and stayed as Grishneshwar (Lord of Compassion). The temple was rebuilt by Ahilyabai Holkar in the 18th century. The red stone architecture is Hemadpanthi style. Its proximity to the Ellora and Ajanta caves makes it a major pilgrimage-cum-heritage destination.' }
  ],
  sapthavidanga: [
    { id: 'sv1', name: 'Thillai Natarajar Temple', location: 'Chidambaram', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Natarajar (Cosmic Dance)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/1.jpg', summary: 'Chitra Sabhai — Shiva performs Ananda Tandava, the Dance of Bliss.', lat: 11.3994, lng: 79.6937, sthalaVaralaru: 'In the Saptha Vidanga tradition, Chidambaram represents the first and most important cosmic dance of Shiva — the Ananda Tandava (Dance of Bliss). Shiva danced here in the golden hall (Ponnambalam) defeating the demon of ignorance (Muyalakan). The dance symbolizes the five cosmic acts: creation, preservation, destruction, concealment, and grace. The temple is the only one where Natarajar (not a lingam) is the main deity.' },
    { id: 'sv2', name: 'Tiruvalangadu Vadaaranyeswarar Temple', location: 'Tiruvalangadu', district: 'Tiruvallur', deity: 'Vadaaranyeswarar (Urdhva Tandava)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/2.jpg', summary: 'Shiva performs Urdhva Tandava — the cosmic dance with leg raised high.', lat: 13.2320, lng: 79.8380, sthalaVaralaru: 'Tiruvalangadu is where Shiva performed the Urdhva Tandava — the victorious dance with one leg raised vertically above his head. He defeated the Goddess Kali in a dance competition here. Kali could not replicate this pose due to modesty, thus conceding defeat. The Chola bronze of Natarajar from this temple (now in Chennai Museum) is considered the finest bronze sculpture ever made. The temple has Chola-period inscriptions.' },
    { id: 'sv3', name: 'Thirukkutralam Kutralanathar Temple', location: 'Courtallam', district: 'Tenkasi', deity: 'Kutralanathar (Trivikrama Tandava)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/3.jpg', summary: 'Shiva performs Trivikrama Tandava near the famous Courtallam Falls.', lat: 8.9330, lng: 77.2780, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Courtallam (Kutralam), Shiva performed the Trivikrama Tandava — a dance form where he measures the cosmos with his cosmic stride, similar to Vishnu\'s Trivikrama form. The temple is near the famous Courtallam waterfalls (Spa of South India). The five waterfalls here are believed to have medicinal properties due to the herbs in the surrounding forests through which the water flows.' },
    { id: 'sv4', name: 'Tiruvarur Thyagarajar Temple', location: 'Tiruvarur', district: 'Tiruvarur', deity: 'Thyagarajar (Ajapa Tandava)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/4.jpg', summary: 'Shiva performs Ajapa Tandava — the silent, subtle dance of breath.', lat: 10.7730, lng: 79.6350, sthalaVaralaru: 'Tiruvarur Thyagarajar Temple is where Shiva performs the Ajapa Tandava — the subtle dance of silent breath, the most mysterious of the seven dances. Thyagaraja (King of Renunciation) dances here without external movement, representing the dance of consciousness itself. The temple has the largest temple tank in Tamil Nadu — Kamalalayam. It was the birthplace of the Chola dynasty and saint Thyagaraja. The Azhivarathal car festival features one of the largest temple chariots.' },
    { id: 'sv5', name: 'Thirunallar Dharbaranyeswarar Temple', location: 'Thirunallar', district: 'Karaikal', deity: 'Dharbaranyeswarar (Muni Tandava)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/5.jpg', summary: 'Shiva performs Muni Tandava — the sage\'s contemplative dance.', lat: 10.8433, lng: 79.8131, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Thirunallar, Shiva performed the Muni Tandava — the contemplative sage\'s dance performed in deep meditation. This is also the famous Sani (Saturn) sthalam. King Nala was freed from Saturn\'s affliction after bathing in the sacred Nala Theertham. The dual significance — as both a Saptha Vidanga and Navagraha temple — makes it one of the most visited temples in the Cauvery delta.' },
    { id: 'sv6', name: 'Nagapattinam Kayarohanaswami Temple', location: 'Nagapattinam', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Kayarohanaswami (Bhujanga Tandava)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/6.jpg', summary: 'Shiva performs Bhujanga Tandava — the serpentine dance.', lat: 10.7650, lng: 79.8420, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Nagapattinam, Shiva performed the Bhujanga Tandava — the serpentine dance where his movements flow like a snake. The name Kayarohana refers to rising from a reclining serpent form. Nagapattinam was an ancient port city with connections to Southeast Asia. The temple has ancient maritime trade inscriptions. The 2004 tsunami affected this coastal temple, which has since been restored.' },
    { id: 'sv7', name: 'Madurai Koodal Azhagar/Nellaiappar Temple', location: 'Tirunelveli', district: 'Tirunelveli', deity: 'Nellaiappar (Hamsa Tandava)', image: 'images/sapthavidanga/7.jpg', summary: 'Shiva performs Hamsa Tandava — the graceful swan-like dance.', lat: 8.7270, lng: 77.6940, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Nellaiappar Temple at Tirunelveli is where Shiva performs the Hamsa Tandava — the graceful dance resembling a swan\'s movements. The temple is a massive complex with the musical pillars — stone columns that produce different musical notes when struck. Built by the Pandya kings, the temple has twin sanctums for Nellaiappar (Shiva) and Kanthimathi Amman (Parvati) connected by a chain-corridor. The Teppam (float) festival on the temple tank is famous.' }
  ],
  sapthasthanam: [
    { id: 'ss1', name: 'Thiruchendur Murugan Temple', location: 'Tiruchendur', district: 'Thoothukudi', deity: 'Senthilandavar', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/1.jpg', summary: 'Where Murugan waged war against the demon Surapadman on the seashore.', lat: 8.4975, lng: 78.1190, sthalaVaralaru: 'Tiruchendur is the primary Saptha Sthanam where Lord Murugan engaged in the final battle with the demon Surapadman on the seashore. The six-day battle is reenacted annually during Skanda Sashti. The demon was split in two — becoming the peacock (vahana) and rooster (flag). The sacred Nazhi Kinaru well inside the temple was created by Murugan\'s Vel (spear) striking the ground to provide fresh water amid the salty sea.' },
    { id: 'ss2', name: 'Thiruthani Murugan Temple', location: 'Thiruthani', district: 'Tiruvallur', deity: 'Murugan with Valli', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/2.jpg', summary: 'Where Murugan rested in solitude after his victory and married Valli.', lat: 13.1750, lng: 79.6120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruthani is where Murugan came to rest in peaceful solitude (Thani = peace/alone) after the war. Here he married Valli, the tribal chieftain\'s daughter. The 365 steps represent each day of the year. The temple is one of the most visited near Chennai and is considered auspicious for marriages. Tuesday is especially sacred here.' },
    { id: 'ss3', name: 'Swamimalai Murugan Temple', location: 'Swamimalai, Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Swaminathan', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/3.jpg', summary: 'Where the child Murugan became Guru to his own father Shiva.', lat: 10.9570, lng: 79.2270, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Swamimalai, the child Murugan taught the meaning of the sacred syllable Om to his own father Shiva, hence called Swaminatha (Guru to the Lord). The 60 steps represent the 60 Tamil years of the Panchangam cycle. The temple sits atop a small hill in the Kumbakonam region. Swamimalai is also world-famous for traditional Chola bronze casting using the lost-wax method.' },
    { id: 'ss4', name: 'Palani Dhandayuthapani Temple', location: 'Palani', district: 'Dindigul', deity: 'Dhandayuthapani', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/4.jpg', summary: 'Where the renunciate Murugan stands with only a staff and loincloth.', lat: 10.4386, lng: 77.5200, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Palani, young Murugan renounced all worldly possessions after the fruit incident and stood atop the hill as an ascetic with only a danda (staff). The Navapashana idol made by Siddhar Bogar from nine poisonous herbs has medicinal properties. The Panchamirtham (five-nectar) prasadam is famous. Thai Pusam and Panguni Uthiram are the major festivals.' },
    { id: 'ss5', name: 'Kundrathur Murugan Temple', location: 'Kundrathur, Chennai', district: 'Chennai', deity: 'Murugan', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/5.jpg', summary: 'Where Murugan halted during his southern march against evil forces.', lat: 12.9940, lng: 80.0990, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kundrathur (hill town) near Chennai is where Murugan paused during his march south to battle the demons. The temple sits on a small hillock and is one of the important Murugan temples near Chennai. The surrounding area was once dense forest. The temple has Pallava-era origins and was expanded during the Chola period.' },
    { id: 'ss6', name: 'Thiruparankundram Murugan Temple', location: 'Thirupparankundram', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Subramanyar', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/6.jpg', summary: 'Where victorious Murugan married Devasena after the cosmic war.', lat: 9.8788, lng: 78.0700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirupparankundram is where Murugan married Devasena after his victory. The rock-cut cave temple is one of the oldest in South India, with shrines for multiple deities carved into the living rock. It is both an Arupadaiveedu and a Saptha Sthanam, making it doubly sacred. The annual Thaipusam festival draws millions.' },
    { id: 'ss7', name: 'Pazhamudhircholai Murugan Temple', location: 'Alagar Hills, Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Murugan', image: 'images/sapthasthanam/7.jpg', summary: 'The sacred fruit grove where Murugan humbled the poet Avvaiyar.', lat: 10.0800, lng: 78.0880, sthalaVaralaru: 'Pazhamudhircholai (grove of ripe fruits) is where young Murugan humbled the elderly poet Avvaiyar, who thought she had mastered all knowledge. He asked her whether she wanted a ripe fruit that had fallen or one still on the tree — a profound philosophical question about the nature of knowledge. The temple is set in dense forest atop the Alagar Hills with a sacred waterfall.' }
  ],
  ashtaveerattanam: [
    { id: 'av1', name: 'Thiruvadhigai Veerattanam', location: 'Thiruvadhigai, near Panruti', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/1.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed Andhakasura, the blind demon of darkness.', lat: 11.7350, lng: 79.5520, sthalaVaralaru: 'The first Ashta Veerattanam where Shiva as Veerattaneswarar destroyed the demon Andhakasura (demon of blindness/darkness). Andhaka was born from the darkness when Parvati covered Shiva\'s eyes playfully. He grew powerful and attempted to kidnap Parvati. Shiva impaled him on his trident and danced the Tandava. The blood-soaked dance here is one of the fiercest forms of Shiva worship.' },
    { id: 'av2', name: 'Thirukkandiyur Veerattanam', location: 'Kandiyur, near Thanjavur', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Brahmashirkandheeswara', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/2.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva cut off one of Brahma\'s five heads.', lat: 10.8310, lng: 79.1080, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Thirukkandiyur, Shiva cut off the fifth head of Brahma. When Brahma grew arrogant and lied about finding the top of the Jyotirlinga, Shiva in his fierce Bhairava form severed Brahma\'s fifth head with his nail. This is why Brahma has only four heads today. Shiva then wandered as a beggar with Brahma\'s skull stuck to his hand until he was absolved at Varanasi.' },
    { id: 'av3', name: 'Thiruvirkolam', location: 'near Cuddalore', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/3.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed the demon Jalandhara.', lat: 11.7250, lng: 79.5270, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Thiruvirkolam, Shiva destroyed the powerful demon Jalandhara who was born from Shiva\'s own anger directed at Indra. Jalandhara became invincible because of his wife Vrinda\'s chastity. When Vishnu broke her chastity through deception, Shiva was able to slay Jalandhara with his Sudarshana Chakra. The demon\'s body fell here and Shiva danced on it in triumph.' },
    { id: 'av4', name: 'Korukkai/Thirukkurukkai', location: 'near Mayiladuthurai', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/4.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed Tripurasura and the three flying cities.', lat: 11.1030, lng: 79.6510, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Thirukkurukkai near Mayiladuthurai, Shiva destroyed the three flying cities (Tripura) of the demons Tarakaksha, Vidyunmali, and Kamalaksha. These golden, silver, and iron cities flew through space and could only be destroyed when aligned. Using Mount Meru as his bow and Vishnu as the arrow, Shiva destroyed all three with a single shot and a smile — hence called Tripurantaka.' },
    { id: 'av5', name: 'Vazhuvur Veerattanam', location: 'Vazhuvur, near Mayiladuthurai', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/5.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed Daksha\'s sacrificial yajna.', lat: 11.0840, lng: 79.6360, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Vazhuvur, Shiva destroyed Daksha\'s grand sacrificial yajna. Daksha, Parvati\'s father, deliberately insulted Shiva by not inviting him to the yajna. Humiliated Sati (Parvati) immolated herself in the sacrificial fire. Enraged Shiva created Virabhadra and Bhadrakali who destroyed the yajna, beheaded Daksha, and terrorized the gods. Later, Shiva restored Daksha with a goat\'s head.' },
    { id: 'av6', name: 'Pariyalur Veerattanam', location: 'Pariyalur, near Sirkazhi', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/6.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed the elephant demon Gajasura.', lat: 11.2050, lng: 79.7190, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Pariyalur, Shiva destroyed the elephant demon Gajasura. The demon had obtained a boon of invincibility and terrorized the worlds. Shiva fought and killed the demon, then wore the elephant skin as a garment (Gajasura Samhara). This fierce form of Shiva wearing the elephant hide is a common motif in temple sculptures across Tamil Nadu.' },
    { id: 'av7', name: 'Thirukkandalam', location: 'near Chidambaram', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/7.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed Kama (God of Love) with his third eye.', lat: 11.3700, lng: 79.6890, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Thirukkandalam, Shiva destroyed Kamadeva (God of Love) by opening his third eye and reducing him to ashes. The gods had sent Kama to disturb Shiva\'s meditation so that he would marry Parvati and father a son (Murugan) who would slay the demon Tarakasura. Though Kama succeeded in awakening desire, Shiva\'s wrathful third-eye fire destroyed him instantly — hence Shiva is called Kama-ari (enemy of Kama).' },
    { id: 'av8', name: 'Thiruppararkundram Veerattanam', location: 'near Thiruvarur', district: 'Tiruvarur', deity: 'Veerattaneswarar', image: 'images/ashtaveerattanam/8.jpg', summary: 'Where Shiva destroyed Yama (God of Death) to save Markandeya.', lat: 10.7590, lng: 79.6270, sthalaVaralaru: 'At Thiruppararkundram, Shiva kicked Yama (God of Death) to save his young devotee Markandeya. The boy was destined to die at age 16 but clung to the Shiva Lingam in desperate devotion. When Yama cast his noose, it fell around both the boy and the lingam. Enraged, Shiva emerged and kicked Yama, saving Markandeya and granting him eternal youth — hence Shiva is called Mrityunjaya (Conqueror of Death) and Kalakala (Death of Death).' }
  ],
  panchasabhai: [
    { id: 'ps1', name: 'Thillai Natarajar Temple (Chitra Sabhai)', location: 'Chidambaram', district: 'Cuddalore', deity: 'Natarajar (Chitra Sabhai — Hall of Pictures)', image: 'images/panchasabhai/1.jpg', summary: 'The Golden Hall (Ponnambalam) where Shiva\'s Ananda Tandava takes place.', lat: 11.3994, lng: 79.6937, sthalaVaralaru: 'Chidambaram\'s Chitra Sabhai (Hall of Pictures/Consciousness) is the most sacred of the Pancha Sabhai. The golden-roofed Ponnambalam houses the dancing Natarajar. The Chidambara Rahasyam — an empty space behind a curtain adorned with golden bilva leaves — represents God as formless cosmic consciousness. The hall is where Shiva performed the Ananda Tandava defeating Muyalakan (ignorance).' },
    { id: 'ps2', name: 'Madurai Meenakshi Temple (Rajata Sabhai)', location: 'Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Sundareswarar (Rajata Sabhai — Silver Hall)', image: 'images/panchasabhai/2.jpg', summary: 'The Silver Hall where Shiva performed the Sandhya Tandava at dusk.', lat: 9.9195, lng: 78.1193, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Rajata Sabhai (Silver Hall) in the Meenakshi Temple is where Shiva as Sundareswarar performs the Sandhya Tandava — the dance of twilight. Every Friday evening, the silver-embossed palanquin of Sundareswarar is carried to Meenakshi\'s chamber in a beautiful ceremony (Oonjal Utsavam). The Silver Hall has exquisite silver-plated columns and ceiling.' },
    { id: 'ps3', name: 'Nellaiappar Temple (Thamira Sabhai)', location: 'Tirunelveli', district: 'Tirunelveli', deity: 'Nellaiappar (Thamira Sabhai — Copper Hall)', image: 'images/panchasabhai/3.jpg', summary: 'The Copper Hall famous for its musical stone pillars.', lat: 8.7270, lng: 77.6940, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Thamira Sabhai (Copper Hall) at Tirunelveli\'s Nellaiappar Temple is famous for its musical pillars — stone columns that produce the seven notes of Indian classical music (Sa Ri Ga Ma Pa Dha Ni) when struck. The hall originally had a copper roof. The twin temples of Nellaiappar and Kanthimathi Amman are connected by a chain-mandapam with 104 musical pillars.' },
    { id: 'ps4', name: 'Kutralam Kutralanathar Temple (Chitra Sabhai)', location: 'Courtallam', district: 'Tenkasi', deity: 'Kutralanathar (Chitra Sabhai — Painted Hall)', image: 'images/panchasabhai/4.jpg', summary: 'The Painted Hall near the famous Courtallam Waterfalls.', lat: 8.9330, lng: 77.2780, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Chitra Sabhai (Painted Hall) at Courtallam features ancient murals depicting Shiva\'s cosmic dances. The temple near the five waterfalls of Courtallam combines spiritual and natural healing — the waterfalls cascade through medicinal herb forests. Shiva performs the Unmatta Tandava (ecstatic dance) here amidst the sound of falling water.' },
    { id: 'ps5', name: 'Vadaranyeswarar Temple (Ratna Sabhai)', location: 'Thiruvalangadu', district: 'Tiruvallur', deity: 'Vadaaranyeswarar (Ratna Sabhai — Jeweled Hall)', image: 'images/panchasabhai/5.jpg', summary: 'The Jeweled Hall where Shiva defeated Kali in the cosmic dance competition.', lat: 13.2320, lng: 79.8380, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Ratna Sabhai (Jeweled/Gem Hall) at Thiruvalangadu is where Shiva\'s Urdhva Tandava defeated Kali in a dance competition. The gods arranged the contest to end Kali\'s fierce destruction. Shiva raised his leg vertically above his head — a pose Kali could not replicate. The Chola Natarajar bronze from this temple is the most celebrated Indian bronze sculpture in existence.' }
  ],
  panchaaranya: [
    { id: 'pa1', name: 'Thiruvanaikaval Jambukeswarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvanaikaval, Trichy', district: 'Tiruchirapalli', deity: 'Jambukeswarar (Jambu Vanam — Jambu Forest)', image: 'images/panchaaranya/1.jpg', summary: 'Shiva in the Jambu (rose apple) tree forest; also a Pancha Bhootha temple.', lat: 10.8535, lng: 78.7066, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvanaikaval represents the Jambu Vanam (Jambu/Rose Apple tree forest). The temple\'s name means "sacred elephant forest" — an elephant and spider were the original devotees. This is also the Appu (Water) Pancha Bhootha Sthalam. The lingam is perpetually immersed in an underground spring that has never dried up. The five enclosures represent the five elements of nature.' },
    { id: 'pa2', name: 'Vedaaranyeswarar Temple', location: 'Vedaranyam', district: 'Nagapattinam', deity: 'Vedaaranyeswarar (Veda Vanam — Vedic Forest)', image: 'images/panchaaranya/2.jpg', summary: 'Shiva in the forest where the Vedas took tree form to worship him.', lat: 10.3680, lng: 79.8520, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vedaranyam represents the Veda Vanam — the sacred forest where the four Vedas took the form of trees and worshipped Lord Shiva. This coastal town on the Bay of Bengal is historically famous as the site of the Salt Satyagraha led by Rajaji in 1930 (parallel to Gandhi\'s Dandi March). The temple has ancient inscriptions and the lingam is believed to be a Swayambhu.' },
    { id: 'pa3', name: 'Dharbaranyeswarar Temple', location: 'Thirunallar', district: 'Karaikal', deity: 'Dharbaranyeswarar (Dharba Vanam — Sacred Grass Forest)', image: 'images/panchaaranya/3.jpg', summary: 'Shiva in the Dharba grass forest; also the Sani (Saturn) sthalam.', lat: 10.8433, lng: 79.8131, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirunallar represents the Dharba Vanam — a forest of sacred Dharba grass used in Vedic rituals. This is also the famous Sani (Saturn) sthalam where King Nala was relieved of his Saturn affliction. The triple significance — Pancha Aranya, Navagraha, and Saptha Vidanga — makes it one of the most important temples in the Cauvery delta.' },
    { id: 'pa4', name: 'Mahavaneshwarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvudal Aarconam', district: 'Ranipet', deity: 'Mahavaneshwarar (Maha Vanam — Great Forest)', image: 'images/panchaaranya/4.jpg', summary: 'Shiva in the Great Forest near Arakkonam.', lat: 13.0780, lng: 79.6690, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvudal Aarconam represents the Maha Vanam — the Great Forest. This temple near Arakkonam was situated in a vast forest in ancient times. Lord Shiva appeared here to sages performing penance in the deep forest. The temple retains its peaceful sylvan atmosphere despite urbanization. The lingam is ancient and believed to pre-date the Pallava period.' },
    { id: 'pa5', name: 'Sundararanyeswarar Temple', location: 'Thenneri', district: 'Tiruvallur', deity: 'Sundararanyeswarar (Sundara Vanam — Beautiful Forest)', image: 'images/panchaaranya/5.jpg', summary: 'Shiva in the Beautiful Forest; the most picturesque of the five.', lat: 13.2250, lng: 79.8300, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thenneri represents the Sundara Vanam — the Beautiful Forest. This temple near Thiruvalangadu was set in a forest of extraordinary beauty. Shiva appeared here in a pleasing, handsome form (Sundara = beautiful) amid flowering trees. The temple is less visited than the others, retaining an air of quiet antiquity. Local tradition associates it with the beauty of the natural world as a reflection of the divine.' }
  ],
  chardham: [
    { id: 'cd1', name: 'Badrinath Temple', location: 'Badrinath, Uttarakhand', district: 'Chamoli', deity: 'Badri Narayana (Vishnu)', image: 'images/chardham/1.jpg', summary: 'Northern Dham at 3,133m; Vishnu meditating in the Himalayas under a Badri tree.', lat: 30.7441, lng: 79.4930, sthalaVaralaru: 'Badrinath in the Himalayas is the northern Char Dham, dedicated to Lord Vishnu. At 3,133 meters, it is one of the holiest Vishnu temples. Narayana chose to meditate here, and Lakshmi transformed into a Badri (berry) tree to shelter him from harsh weather. Adi Shankaracharya rediscovered the deity in the Alaknanda river and established the temple. The natural hot spring Tapta Kund provides warm water even in freezing temperatures. Open only May to November.' },
    { id: 'cd2', name: 'Jagannath Temple', location: 'Puri, Odisha', district: 'Puri', deity: 'Jagannath (Krishna/Vishnu)', image: 'images/chardham/2.jpg', summary: 'Eastern Dham; home of the famous Rath Yatra festival and the Jagannath cult.', lat: 19.8048, lng: 85.8181, sthalaVaralaru: 'Jagannath Puri is the eastern Char Dham, one of the most sacred Hindu temples. Lord Jagannath (Krishna), Balabhadra, and Subhadra are worshipped here as wooden deities that are ceremonially replaced every 12-19 years (Nabakalebara). The annual Rath Yatra (Chariot Festival) is one of the world\'s largest religious gatherings — the English word "Juggernaut" derives from Jagannath. The temple\'s flag always flutters in the opposite direction of the wind. Built by King Anantavarman Chodaganga in the 12th century.' },
    { id: 'cd3', name: 'Dwarkadhish Temple', location: 'Dwarka, Gujarat', district: 'Devbhoomi Dwarka', deity: 'Dwarkadhish (Krishna)', image: 'images/chardham/3.jpg', summary: 'Western Dham; Krishna\'s legendary golden city, partially submerged in the sea.', lat: 22.2374, lng: 68.9672, sthalaVaralaru: 'Dwarka is the western Char Dham, the legendary golden city built by Lord Krishna. After leaving Mathura, Krishna established Dwarka as his capital on the coast of the Arabian Sea. The original city is believed to be submerged — marine archaeological surveys have found underwater structures matching the descriptions in the Mahabharata. The five-story Dwarkadhish Temple with its 78-meter flag post (Dhwaja) is visible from far at sea. The Gomti river meets the sea here.' },
    { id: 'cd4', name: 'Ramanathaswamy Temple', location: 'Rameswaram, Tamil Nadu', district: 'Ramanathapuram', deity: 'Ramanathaswamy (Shiva)', image: 'images/chardham/4.jpg', summary: 'Southern Dham; Shiva Lingam installed by Lord Rama with the longest temple corridor.', lat: 9.2881, lng: 79.3174, sthalaVaralaru: 'Rameswaram is the southern Char Dham, uniquely dedicated to Shiva (while the other three are Vishnu temples). Lord Rama installed the Shiva Lingam here to seek absolution for killing Ravana. The temple has the world\'s longest corridor (1,220 meters) with intricately carved pillars. The 22 sacred wells (theerthams) within the temple complex each have different mineral compositions and healing properties. Rameswaram is connected to mainland India by the Pamban Bridge.' }
  ],
  shaktipeethas: [
    { id: 'sp1', name: 'Kamakshi Amman Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Kamakshi (Navel/Manipura)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/1.jpg', summary: 'One of the 3 main Shakti Peethas; Sati\'s navel fell here.', lat: 12.8423, lng: 79.7125, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kamakshi Amman Temple at Kanchipuram is one of the three primary Shakti Peethas (the others being Meenakshi at Madurai and Visalakshi at Varanasi). According to the Daksha Yagna legend, when Vishnu\'s Sudarshana Chakra dismembered Sati\'s body to stop Shiva\'s tandava of grief, her navel (Manipura) fell at Kanchipuram. Adi Shankaracharya installed the Sri Chakra here to pacify the Goddess from Ugra to Shanta form.' },
    { id: 'sp2', name: 'Meenakshi Amman Temple', location: 'Madurai', district: 'Madurai', deity: 'Meenakshi (Shakti Peetha)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/2.jpg', summary: 'Major Shakti Peetha; the fish-eyed Goddess who ruled Madurai.', lat: 9.9195, lng: 78.1193, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Meenakshi Amman Temple at Madurai is a major Shakti Peetha. Meenakshi (fish-eyed Goddess) was born with three breasts from a yajna fire. She conquered the world and challenged Shiva himself, but when she met him, her third breast vanished and she recognized her divine consort. The temple has 14 gopurams, 33,000 sculptures, and the famous Golden Lotus Tank. The Chithirai festival celebrating the divine wedding draws millions.' },
    { id: 'sp3', name: 'Visalakshi Temple', location: 'Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh', district: 'Varanasi', deity: 'Visalakshi (Wide-eyed Goddess)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/3.jpg', summary: 'One of the 3 main Shakti Peethas in the holiest city; Sati\'s earrings fell here.', lat: 25.3095, lng: 83.0080, sthalaVaralaru: 'Visalakshi Temple in Varanasi is the third of the primary trinity of Shakti Peethas. Sati\'s earrings are said to have fallen here. Located near the Kashi Vishwanath Temple in the spiritual heart of Varanasi, Visalakshi (wide-eyed Goddess) watches over the holiest city. The temple has been a center of Shakti worship for millennia. Navaratri celebrations here are among the most elaborate in India.' },
    { id: 'sp4', name: 'Kalighat Kali Temple', location: 'Kolkata, West Bengal', district: 'Kolkata', deity: 'Kali (Dakshina Kali)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/4.jpg', summary: 'Where Sati\'s right toe fell; origin of Kolkata\'s name.', lat: 22.5199, lng: 88.3425, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kalighat Kali Temple is one of the 51 Shakti Peethas where Sati\'s right toes fell. The city of Kolkata (Calcutta) derives its name from Kalighat. The temple houses Dakshina Kali — the benevolent form of the fierce Goddess Kali. The present temple was built in 1809. It is the most important Kali temple in the world. Mother Teresa\'s Missionaries of Charity home is nearby, named Nirmal Hriday (Pure Heart).' },
    { id: 'sp5', name: 'Naina Devi Temple', location: 'Bilaspur, Himachal Pradesh', district: 'Bilaspur', deity: 'Naina Devi (Eyes of Sati)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/5.jpg', summary: 'Where Sati\'s eyes fell atop a hill overlooking Gobind Sagar Lake.', lat: 31.3140, lng: 76.5330, sthalaVaralaru: 'Naina Devi Temple atop a hill overlooking Gobind Sagar Lake is where Sati\'s eyes (Naina = eyes) fell. The hilltop temple offers panoramic views of the Himalayan foothills. During the Shravana Ashtami fair, hundreds of thousands of pilgrims climb the hill. The Goddess is flanked by Ganesha and Hanuman. The temple was destroyed in the 1905 Kangra earthquake and rebuilt.' },
    { id: 'sp6', name: 'Jwala Ji Temple', location: 'Kangra, Himachal Pradesh', district: 'Kangra', deity: 'Jwala Devi (Eternal Flame)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/6.jpg', summary: 'Where Sati\'s tongue fell; eternal natural gas flames burn without fuel.', lat: 31.8740, lng: 76.3100, sthalaVaralaru: 'Jwala Ji Temple is where Sati\'s tongue fell. The deity is not an idol but eternal natural gas flames (Jwalas) that burn continuously from nine openings in the rock without any fuel source. Akbar tried to extinguish the flames by diverting a water channel but failed. He then offered a golden umbrella (chattra) which the Goddess rejected — it transformed into an unknown metal. The eternal flame is one of the most miraculous phenomena in Hindu temples.' },
    { id: 'sp7', name: 'Chamundeshwari Temple', location: 'Mysore, Karnataka', district: 'Mysore', deity: 'Chamundeshwari (Durga)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/7.jpg', summary: 'Where Sati\'s hair fell atop Chamundi Hill; presiding deity of Mysore.', lat: 12.2725, lng: 76.6700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Chamundeshwari Temple atop Chamundi Hill (1,065 meters) in Mysore is where Sati\'s hair fell. Chamundi is the fierce form of Durga who slew the buffalo demon Mahishasura — Mysore (Mahisuru) is named after this demon. The Nandi Bull statue on the hill path is one of the largest in India. The Mysore Dasara festival celebrates Chamundeshwari\'s victory over Mahishasura with a grand procession of the golden howdah.' },
    { id: 'sp8', name: 'Bhramaramba Temple', location: 'Srisailam, Andhra Pradesh', district: 'Kurnool', deity: 'Bhramaramba (Bee Goddess)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/8.jpg', summary: 'Shakti Peetha alongside the Mallikarjuna Jyotirlinga at Srisailam.', lat: 16.0744, lng: 78.8686, sthalaVaralaru: 'Bhramaramba Temple at Srisailam is one of the 18 Maha Shakti Peethas, uniquely co-located with the Mallikarjuna Jyotirlinga. Sati\'s neck is said to have fallen here. Bhramaramba means "Mother in the form of a bee" — the Goddess appeared as a swarm of bees to destroy the demon Arunasura. Srisailam is one of only two places in India where both a Jyotirlinga and Shakti Peetha exist together.' },
    { id: 'sp9', name: 'Tarapith Temple', location: 'Birbhum, West Bengal', district: 'Birbhum', deity: 'Tara Ma (Tantric Goddess)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/9.jpg', summary: 'Where Sati\'s third eye fell; center of Tantric worship in Bengal.', lat: 24.0010, lng: 87.8810, sthalaVaralaru: 'Tarapith is where Sati\'s third eye (the eye of wisdom) fell. The temple is the most important center of Tantric worship in Bengal. The famous saint Bamakhepa (the mad saint) practiced extreme Tantric sadhana at the adjacent cremation ground. The deity Tara Ma is worshipped in her Ugra (fierce) form. The Goddess is depicted with four arms, seated on a lotus, with the infant Shiva on her lap. The cremation ground adjoining the temple is still used for Tantric practices.' },
    { id: 'sp10', name: 'Ambaji Temple', location: 'Ambaji, Gujarat', district: 'Banaskantha', deity: 'Ambaji Mata (Shakti)', image: 'images/shaktipeethas/10.jpg', summary: 'Where Sati\'s heart fell; one of the most visited Shakti shrines in Gujarat.', lat: 24.3310, lng: 72.8480, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ambaji Temple in Gujarat is where Sati\'s heart fell. Uniquely, there is no idol here — the Goddess is worshipped as a sacred Visha Yantra (a gold-plated geometric diagram). The temple sits atop the Aravalli Hills at the border of Gujarat and Rajasthan. Gabbar Hill nearby has a shrine to the Goddess visited by millions during Navaratri. The Ambaji fair during Bhadarvi Purnima is one of the largest religious fairs in Gujarat.' }
  ],
  navatirupathi: [
    { id: 'nt1', name: 'Sri Vaikundanatha Perumal Temple', location: 'Sri Vaikundam', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Vaikuntanathan (Seated)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/1.jpg', summary: 'First Nava Tirupathi; the gateway to heaven brought to earth.', lat: 8.7370, lng: 77.8600, sthalaVaralaru: 'Sri Vaikundam is the first of the nine Nava Tirupathis in the Tirunelveli region. The Lord brought Vaikuntham (heaven) itself to this earthly spot. These 9 Divya Desams, all sung by Nammazhwar, can be visited in a single day in a ~100 km round trip from Tirunelveli. The circuit starts here and ends at Alwar Thirunagiri.' },
    { id: 'nt2', name: 'Sri Vijayaasana Perumal Temple', location: 'Thiruvaragunamangai', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Vijayaasanar (Seated)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/2.jpg', summary: 'Second Nava Tirupathi; Lord on the victory throne.', lat: 8.7260, lng: 77.8700, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvaragunamangai is the second Nava Tirupathi. The Lord sits on a Vijayasanam (victory throne) having conquered all evil. Nammazhwar composed beautiful verses about this temple describing the Lord\'s majestic posture and the beauty of the surrounding landscape. The temple is just 2 km from Sri Vaikundam.' },
    { id: 'nt3', name: 'Sri Kaaichina Vendha Perumal Temple', location: 'Thiruppulingudu', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Kaaisina Vendhan (Standing)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/3.jpg', summary: 'Third Nava Tirupathi; the victorious angry king who destroys evil.', lat: 8.7200, lng: 77.8750, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruppulingudu is the third Nava Tirupathi. The Lord appears as Kaaisina Vendhan — the angry victorious king who destroys evil forces threatening his devotees. The fierce but protective form shows the Lord\'s readiness to battle for righteousness. The temple is 1 km from the previous one.' },
    { id: 'nt4', name: 'Sri Srinivasa Perumal Temple', location: 'Thirukkulanthai', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Srinivasan (Standing)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/4.jpg', summary: 'Fourth Nava Tirupathi; the Lord as a divine child.', lat: 8.6850, lng: 77.8560, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirukkulanthai is the fourth Nava Tirupathi. The Lord appears in the endearing form of a divine child (Kulanthai = child). The innocent and loving form attracts devotees seeking the Lord\'s gentle grace. The temple is 10 km from Thiruppulingudu.' },
    { id: 'nt5', name: 'Sri Aravindha Lochana Perumal Temple', location: 'Thiruttholai Villimangalam', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Aravinda Lochanan (Standing)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/5.jpg', summary: 'Fifth Nava Tirupathi; the lotus-eyed Lord.', lat: 8.6300, lng: 77.8680, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruttholai Villimangalam is the fifth Nava Tirupathi. The Lord\'s lotus-shaped eyes (Aravinda Lochana) captivated all who beheld him. Nammazhwar specifically praised the beauty of the Lord\'s eyes in his pasurams. The temple is in a remote, serene setting.' },
    { id: 'nt6', name: 'Sri Makara Nedunkuzhai Kaathar Temple', location: 'Then Thirupperai', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Makara Nedunkuzhaikkathar (Standing)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/6.jpg', summary: 'Sixth Nava Tirupathi; Lord adorned with fish-shaped earrings.', lat: 8.6100, lng: 77.8550, sthalaVaralaru: 'Then Thirupperai is the sixth Nava Tirupathi. The Lord wears distinctive Makara (fish-shaped) long earrings (Nedunkuzhai). This unique ornamentation is rarely seen in other Vishnu temples. The fish-shaped earrings symbolize the Matsya (fish) avatar and the Lord\'s mastery over the ocean of existence.' },
    { id: 'nt7', name: 'Sri Vaitha Maanitha Perumal Temple', location: 'Thirukkoloor', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Vaithamanidhi (Reclining)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/7.jpg', summary: 'Seventh Nava Tirupathi; famous for the girl\'s 81 philosophical questions.', lat: 8.5400, lng: 77.6400, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thirukkoloor is the seventh Nava Tirupathi, famous for the Thirukkolur Pen Pillai Rahasyam — 81 profound philosophical questions posed by a young girl to Ramanuja. Each question references a great devotee or sage, asking "What have I done to deserve being here?" The Lord as Vaithamanidhi (deposited treasure) rests here preserving all spiritual wealth.' },
    { id: 'nt8', name: 'Sri Aadhinatha Swamy Temple', location: 'Alwar Thirunagiri', district: 'Tuticorin', deity: 'Aadhirathar (Standing)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/8.jpg', summary: 'Eighth Nava Tirupathi; birthplace of Nammazhwar, the greatest Azhwar.', lat: 8.5240, lng: 77.6160, sthalaVaralaru: 'Alwar Thirunagiri is the eighth Nava Tirupathi and the birthplace of Nammazhwar, the greatest of the 12 Azhwars. Nammazhwar sat under a tamarind tree for 16 years in divine meditation before being awakened by Madhurakavi Azhwar. He then composed 1,296 pasurams including the Thiruvaimozhi. The tamarind tree still stands as a living monument to his devotion.' },
    { id: 'nt9', name: 'Sri Thothadrinatha Perumal Temple', location: 'Thenthirupperai (Nanguneri)', district: 'Tirunelveli', deity: 'Thothadrinathar (Standing)', image: 'images/navatirupathi/9.jpg', summary: 'Ninth and final Nava Tirupathi; seat of the Thenkalai Vaishnavite tradition.', lat: 8.3720, lng: 77.4730, sthalaVaralaru: 'Nanguneri (Thenthirupperai) is the ninth and final Nava Tirupathi. While technically separate from the cluster (it is 40 km from Tirunelveli), it completes the Nava Tirupathi circuit. This is the headquarters of the Thenkalai (southern school) Sri Vaishnavite tradition established by Manavala Mamunigal. The temple is a major monastery and center of Vaishnavite learning.' }
  ],
  kumbakonam: [
    { id: 'kbk1', name: 'Adi Kumbeswarar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Kumbeswarar)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/1.jpg', summary: 'The main temple of Kumbakonam, associated with the Mahamaham festival held every 12 years.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.9617, lng: 79.3881, sthalaVaralaru: 'Adi Kumbeswarar Temple is the principal temple of Kumbakonam and gives the city its name. According to legend, during the great deluge (Pralaya), Lord Brahma placed the seeds of creation in a pot (Kumbha) and set it afloat. Lord Shiva as a hunter shot an arrow that broke the pot at this location, and the nectar (amrit) from it formed the Mahamaham tank. The Shiva Lingam here was formed from the nectar mixed with sand. The Mahamaham festival, held every 12 years when Jupiter transits Leo, draws millions of devotees who bathe in the sacred tank. The temple covers over 4 acres with a towering 9-tier rajagopuram. The Nayak kings extensively renovated the temple in the 17th century.' },
    { id: 'kbk2', name: 'Sarangapani Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Sarangapani)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/2.jpg', summary: 'One of the 108 Divya Desams; the largest Vishnu temple in Kumbakonam with the tallest gopuram.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.9603, lng: 79.3908, sthalaVaralaru: 'Sarangapani Temple is one of the 108 Divya Desams sung by Azhwar saints and the largest Vaishnavite temple in Kumbakonam. The 11-tiered rajagopuram (173 feet) is one of the tallest in South India. The Lord here is Sarangapani — the one who holds the bow called Saranga. According to the sthala purana, Goddess Lakshmi performed penance here to be reunited with Lord Vishnu after being cursed by Sage Bhrigu. The temple tank, Porthamarai Kulam, is shaped like a lotus. The temple has exquisite Nayak-period sculptures and was praised by the Azhwar saint Thirumangai.' },
    { id: 'kbk3', name: 'Chakrapani Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Chakrapani)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/3.jpg', summary: 'Rare Divya Desam where Vishnu\'s Sudarshana Chakra (discus) is the main deity.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9625, lng: 79.3830, sthalaVaralaru: 'Chakrapani Temple is one of the few temples where Lord Vishnu\'s weapon, the Sudarshana Chakra (divine discus), is worshipped as the presiding deity. This is one of the 108 Divya Desams. According to legend, when the Sudarshana Chakra was exhausted after destroying the demon Jalandhara, it came to Kumbakonam to regain its power by worshipping Lord Shiva. The Chakra is enshrined with 16 arms, each holding a different weapon. The temple has beautiful Vijayanagara and Nayak period architecture.' },
    { id: 'kbk4', name: 'Nageswaran Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Nageswaran)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/4.jpg', summary: 'Ancient Chola temple with UNESCO heritage; famous for the solar alignment during Chitra Pournami.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9640, lng: 79.3860, sthalaVaralaru: 'Nageswaran Temple (also known as Sundareswarar Temple) is one of the oldest Shiva temples in Kumbakonam, dating to the early Chola period (886 CE). The temple is remarkable for its astronomical alignment — during Chitra Pournami (April full moon), sunlight falls directly on the Shiva Lingam through a window, creating a natural spotlight. This phenomenon demonstrates the scientific knowledge of ancient temple architects. The temple has exquisite Chola-era stone carvings and bronze sculptures. It is part of the UNESCO Great Living Chola Temples heritage cluster.' },
    { id: 'kbk5', name: 'Ramaswamy Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Rama', image: 'images/kumbakonam/5.jpg', summary: 'Stunning Nayak-era temple with corridors depicting the entire Ramayana in paintings and sculptures.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9590, lng: 79.3870, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ramaswamy Temple is a magnificent Nayak-period temple dedicated to Lord Rama, built in the 16th century. The temple is renowned for its stunning corridors lined with sculpted pillars depicting episodes from the Ramayana. The ceiling paintings narrate the complete story of Rama in vivid detail. The mandapam has 220 exquisitely carved pillars, each telling a story. The temple features life-size sculptures of Rama, Sita, Lakshmana, and Hanuman. The Nayak artisans created some of the finest narrative sculpture art found anywhere in South India.' },
    { id: 'kbk6', name: 'Kasi Viswanathar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Viswanathar)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/6.jpg', summary: 'Kumbakonam\'s Kasi — a replica of the Varanasi Vishwanath temple offering the same spiritual merit.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9605, lng: 79.3895, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kasi Viswanathar Temple is believed to bestow the same spiritual merit as worshipping at the Kashi Vishwanath Temple in Varanasi. According to legend, Lord Shiva blessed this location such that worship here equals a pilgrimage to Kashi. The temple was built during the Chola period and expanded by Nayak rulers. It is especially popular among devotees who cannot travel to Varanasi. The temple has a beautiful tank and ornate mandapam.' },
    { id: 'kbk7', name: 'Uppiliappan Temple', location: 'Thirunageswaram (near Kumbakonam)', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Uppiliappan)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/7.jpg', summary: 'Famous Divya Desam where prasadam is prepared without salt, as promised by Lord Vishnu.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 10.9340, lng: 79.3230, sthalaVaralaru: 'Uppiliappan Temple (Uppili = without salt) is a unique Divya Desam where all temple offerings and prasadam are prepared without salt. Lord Vishnu married Markandeya\'s adopted daughter Bhumi Devi, and the sage, worried about the bride\'s age, asked the Lord to accept the girl "as is" (uppu + ili = without salt/additions). The Lord agreed, and to this day, no salt is used in any temple food. This is one of the most visited temples in the Kumbakonam belt. The temple has stunning Chola and Nayak architecture with a grand vimana.' },
    { id: 'kbk8', name: 'Airavatesvara Temple', location: 'Darasuram (near Kumbakonam)', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Airavatesvara)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/8.jpg', summary: 'UNESCO World Heritage Site built by Rajaraja Chola II; a masterpiece of Chola art and architecture.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 6:00 PM', lat: 10.9475, lng: 79.3527, sthalaVaralaru: 'Airavatesvara Temple at Darasuram is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, part of the Great Living Chola Temples. Built by Rajaraja Chola II in the 12th century, this architectural marvel features a chariot-shaped mandapam pulled by horses and elephants. The temple gets its name from Airavata, the white elephant of Indra, who worshipped Shiva here. The Agra mandapam (front hall) is designed as a massive stone chariot. The temple has exquisite stone carvings showing dancers, musicians, acrobats, and mythological scenes. The musical steps at the entrance produce different musical notes when tapped.' },
    { id: 'kbk9', name: 'Mahalingeswarar Temple', location: 'Thiruvidaimarudur (near Kumbakonam)', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Mahalingam)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/9.jpg', summary: 'One of the largest Shiva temples in the Cauvery delta with a massive 11-acre complex.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9951, lng: 79.4538, sthalaVaralaru: 'Mahalingeswarar Temple at Thiruvidaimarudur is one of the largest Shiva temple complexes in the Cauvery delta region, covering over 11 acres. The temple is a Paadal Petra Sthalam sung by all three Thevaram saints — Appar, Sundarar, and Sambandhar. According to legend, Lord Shiva appeared here in a massive form (Mahalingam) to bless the sages. The temple has inscriptions from the reigns of Rajaraja Chola I and Rajendra Chola I. The Navarathri celebrations here are famous.' },
    { id: 'kbk10', name: 'Someswara Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Someswara)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/10.jpg', summary: 'Ancient temple where Chandra (Moon God) worshipped Shiva; part of the Navagraha belt.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9580, lng: 79.3850, sthalaVaralaru: 'Someswara Temple is an ancient Shiva temple where Soma (Chandra/Moon God) worshipped Lord Shiva to be relieved of Daksha\'s curse. The moon god\'s waxing and waning cycle is said to have been established here. The temple is part of the sacred temple circuit of Kumbakonam and has beautiful Chola-period architecture. It is closely connected to the Navagraha temple tradition of the region. The temple tank is considered sacred for moon-related rituals.' },
    { id: 'kbk11', name: 'Abhimukeswarar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Abhimukeswarar)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/11.jpg', summary: 'Temple where the Shiva Lingam is said to face all directions simultaneously, granting darshan to all.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9610, lng: 79.3840, sthalaVaralaru: 'Abhimukeswarar Temple houses a unique Shiva Lingam that is said to face all directions simultaneously (Abhimukha = facing towards). This means the Lord grants darshan to devotees from every direction — a spiritually significant concept. The temple is mentioned in Thevaram hymns and is part of the ancient Kumbakonam temple network. The Chola-era structure has been well preserved. Devotees visit this temple to seek Shiva\'s direct grace and blessings.' },
    { id: 'kbk12', name: 'Swamimalai Murugan Temple', location: 'Swamimalai (near Kumbakonam)', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Murugan (Swaminathan)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/12.jpg', summary: 'Fourth Arupadaiveedu — where child Murugan taught the meaning of Om to Lord Shiva.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 10.9570, lng: 79.2270, sthalaVaralaru: 'Swamimalai is the fourth of the six Arupadaiveedu (battle camps) of Lord Murugan. Here, the child Murugan taught the meaning of Pranava mantra (Om) to his own father Lord Shiva, earning the name Swaminathan (Lord who became Guru to his father). The temple sits atop a small hillock reached by climbing 60 steps representing the 60 Tamil years (Thiruvalluvar cycle). The town is also world-famous for its traditional bronze casting artisans who use the ancient Chola lost-wax technique to create stunning temple bronzes that are exported worldwide.' },
    { id: 'kbk13', name: 'Banapuriswarar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Banapuriswarar)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/13.jpg', summary: 'Historic Chola-era Shiva temple in the heart of Kumbakonam with inscriptions of Rajaraja Chola.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9620, lng: 79.3870, sthalaVaralaru: 'Banapuriswarar Temple is one of the historic Shiva temples in the heart of Kumbakonam town. The temple dates to the Chola period with inscriptions from the reigns of Rajaraja Chola I and Kulottunga Chola I. The name Banapuri refers to the forest (vana/bana) that once surrounded this area. The temple has well-preserved Chola-era stone carvings and a sacred tank. It is part of the dense network of temples that earned Kumbakonam its title as the Temple Town of Tamil Nadu.' },
    { id: 'kbk14', name: 'Gauthameswarar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Gauthameswarar)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/14.jpg', summary: 'Temple where Sage Gautama worshipped Shiva; located near the sacred Mahamaham tank.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9615, lng: 79.3878, sthalaVaralaru: 'Gauthameswarar Temple is where Sage Gautama (of Gautama Dharmasutra fame) worshipped Lord Shiva. The temple is located near the sacred Mahamaham tank and is part of the network of temples surrounding the tank. Sage Gautama is believed to have performed intense penance here and was blessed by Lord Shiva. The temple has inscriptions from the later Chola period. During the Mahamaham festival, this temple is part of the sacred circuit that devotees follow.' },
    { id: 'kbk15', name: 'Patteeswarar Temple', location: 'Kumbakonam', district: 'Thanjavur', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Thenupuriswarar)', image: 'images/kumbakonam/15.jpg', summary: 'One of the largest Shiva temples in the region, covering over 10 acres with massive gopurams.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 10.9300, lng: 79.2800, sthalaVaralaru: 'The Patteeswarar Temple (Thenupuriswarar) is one of the largest temple complexes in the Kumbakonam region, covering over 10 acres. The presiding deity Thenupuriswarar (Lord of the southern city) is also known as Patteeswarar. The temple has massive gopurams, extensive mandapams, and beautiful Chola-era sculptures. Inscriptions from Rajaraja Chola I and Rajendra Chola I document extensive donations to this temple. The Vinayagar shrine here is also separately famous. The temple is a Paadal Petra Sthalam praised in Thevaram hymns.' }
  ],
  kanchipuram: [
    { id: 'knc1', name: 'Ekambareswarar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Prithvi Lingam)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/1.jpg', summary: 'Pancha Bhootha Sthalam (Earth element); one of the largest temples in India covering 25 acres.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.8520, lng: 79.7006, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ekambareswarar Temple represents Prithvi (Earth) among the Pancha Bhootha Sthalams and is the largest temple in Kanchipuram, covering 25 acres. Goddess Parvati made a Shiva Lingam from sand under a sacred mango tree here. Lord Shiva tested her by sending fire and flood, but she embraced the lingam, leaving her marks on it. The temple has a towering 11-tier rajagopuram (59 meters) and the sacred mango tree is believed to be 3,500 years old, with four branches representing the four Vedas, each yielding differently flavored fruits. The temple has over 1,000 inscriptions documenting its patronage by Pallava, Chola, Vijayanagara, and Nayak dynasties.' },
    { id: 'knc2', name: 'Kamakshi Amman Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Goddess Kamakshi (Tripurasundari)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/2.jpg', summary: 'One of the three major Shakti Peethas; where Adi Shankaracharya established the Sri Chakra.', timings: 'Morning: 5:30 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:30 PM', lat: 12.8425, lng: 79.7126, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kamakshi Amman Temple is one of the three holiest Shakti Peethas in India, along with Visalakshi (Varanasi) and Meenakshi (Madurai). The Goddess is worshipped as Kamakshi — the one whose eyes radiate love and desire (Kama = desire, Akshi = eyes). Adi Shankaracharya established the Sri Chakra (sacred geometric diagram) here to calm the fierce energy of the Goddess. He also established one of his four Shankaracharya Mathas (Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham) here. The Goddess is depicted in Padmasana (seated lotus posture), which is rare for Shakti temples. The annual Brahmotsavam and Navaratri festivals attract hundreds of thousands of devotees.' },
    { id: 'knc3', name: 'Varadharaja Perumal Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Varadharaja)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/3.jpg', summary: 'One of the 108 Divya Desams; famous for the Athi Varadhar festival held once every 40 years.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:30 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 9:00 PM', lat: 12.8360, lng: 79.7234, sthalaVaralaru: 'Varadharaja Perumal Temple is one of the most important Divya Desams and the principal Vishnu temple in Kanchipuram. The deity Varadharaja (bestower of boons) is seen giving blessings in a standing posture. The temple is famous for the Athi Varadhar — a sacred fig-wood idol of Vishnu submerged in the temple tank, which is taken out and displayed only once every 40 years for 48 days. When this happened in 2019, over 25 million devotees visited. The temple has a magnificent 100-pillar hall with exquisite sculptures. It was patronized by Pallava, Chola, and Vijayanagara kings.' },
    { id: 'knc4', name: 'Kailasanathar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Kailasanathar)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/4.jpg', summary: 'The oldest structural temple in Kanchipuram; a Pallava masterpiece built by Rajasimha in 685 CE.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8537, lng: 79.6980, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kailasanathar Temple is the oldest structural (non-rock-cut) temple in Kanchipuram, built by Pallava king Narasimhavarman II (Rajasimha) around 685 CE. It is a masterpiece of early Dravidian architecture that influenced all subsequent South Indian temple building. The temple has 58 small shrines along its inner walls, each housing a different form of Shiva. The sandstone carvings are among the finest examples of Pallava art, depicting scenes from the lives of Shiva and Parvati. A narrow circumambulation passage runs behind the main shrine — pilgrims crawl through it as a spiritual experience. The temple remains largely unaltered, making it invaluable for understanding Pallava architecture.' },
    { id: 'knc5', name: 'Vaikunta Perumal Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Vaikuntanathan)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/5.jpg', summary: 'Pallava architectural marvel with three tiers showing Vishnu in sitting, standing, and reclining forms.', timings: 'Morning: 8:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 7:30 PM', lat: 12.8432, lng: 79.7108, sthalaVaralaru: 'Vaikunta Perumal Temple was built by Pallava king Nandivarman II around 740 CE and is one of the finest examples of Pallava temple architecture. The temple is unique for its three-tiered sanctum — the ground floor shows Lord Vishnu seated, the second floor standing, and the top floor reclining. This represents the three aspects of the Lord in Vaikuntham (heaven). The temple\'s outer walls have detailed sculptural panels depicting the political history of the Pallavas, making it a rare historical document carved in stone. The cloister mandapam has lion pillars that are a hallmark of Pallava art.' },
    { id: 'knc6', name: 'Ulagalantha Perumal Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Trivikrama)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/6.jpg', summary: 'Divya Desam celebrating Vishnu\'s Trivikrama (Vamana) avatar who measured the three worlds.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8420, lng: 79.7150, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ulagalantha Perumal Temple is a Divya Desam dedicated to Lord Vishnu in his Trivikrama form — the cosmic giant who measured the three worlds in three strides. The deity stands with one foot on the earth and the other reaching the heavens, depicting the moment when Vamana (dwarf avatar) transformed into the universe-spanning Trivikrama to humble the demon king Mahabali. The temple was sung by Thirumangai Azhwar and Peyazhwar. It has beautiful Chola and Vijayanagara period sculptures depicting the Vamana avatar story.' },
    { id: 'knc7', name: 'Ashtabujakaram Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Ashtabhuja Perumal)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/7.jpg', summary: 'Rare Divya Desam where Vishnu appears with eight arms, holding weapons and divine emblems.', timings: 'Morning: 6:30 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:30 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8380, lng: 79.7130, sthalaVaralaru: 'Ashtabujakaram Temple is a Divya Desam where Lord Vishnu is worshipped in a rare eight-armed (Ashta Bhuja) form. Each arm holds a different divine weapon or emblem — Sudarshana Chakra, Conch (Shankha), Mace (Gada), Sword (Khadga), Bow (Sharanga), Arrow, Shield, and Lotus. This form represents the Lord\'s complete cosmic power. The temple was praised by Thirumangai Azhwar. This rare iconographic form makes it one of the most unique Vishnu temples in India.' },
    { id: 'knc8', name: 'Yathothkari Perumal Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Yathothkari)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/8.jpg', summary: 'Divya Desam where Vishnu appeared to save a devotee from a charging elephant.', timings: 'Morning: 7:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 7:30 PM', lat: 12.8390, lng: 79.7120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Yathothkari Perumal Temple is a Divya Desam where the Lord rushed (Yathothkari = one who came swiftly) to save his devotee Gajendra (the elephant king) from the grip of a crocodile. The temple celebrates the famous Gajendra Moksha episode from the Bhagavata Purana. The deity is in a dynamic pose, depicting the urgency of the Lord rushing to save his devotee. This was sung by Peyazhwar. The temple emphasizes the Lord\'s unconditional love for his devotees.' },
    { id: 'knc9', name: 'Pandava Thoothar Perumal Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Krishna (Pandava Thoothar)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/9.jpg', summary: 'Divya Desam where Krishna is worshipped as the Pandavas\' messenger to the Kauravas.', timings: 'Morning: 7:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 7:30 PM', lat: 12.8400, lng: 79.7100, sthalaVaralaru: 'Pandava Thoothar Temple is a unique Divya Desam where Lord Krishna is worshipped as the messenger (Thoothar = ambassador) sent by the Pandavas to the Kauravas before the Mahabharata war. The deity depicts Krishna in his role as the divine diplomat who tried to prevent the war. When the Kauravas rejected peace, Krishna revealed his Vishwaroopa (cosmic universal form) in the Kaurava court. The temple was praised by Thirumangai Azhwar. This is one of the rare temples depicting Krishna in his diplomatic avatar rather than his commonly worshipped forms.' },
    { id: 'knc10', name: 'Thiruvekkaa (Yathoktakari) Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Vishnu (Sonna Vannam Seitha Perumal)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/10.jpg', summary: 'Divya Desam where Vishnu did exactly as Saraswati asked — reclining on the sacred Vegavathi river.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8500, lng: 79.7050, sthalaVaralaru: 'Thiruvekkaa Temple is a Divya Desam where the Lord is known as Sonna Vannam Seitha Perumal — "the Lord who did exactly as told." When Goddess Saraswati and Goddess Lakshmi competed to host the Lord, Saraswati asked him to recline on her river (Vegavathi). The Lord obliged, and remains in a reclining posture here. It was praised by Poigaiazhwar and Thirumangai Azhwar. The temple tank is the Vegavathi river itself. The temple has beautiful Pallava and Chola architecture.' },
    { id: 'knc11', name: 'Kumara Kottam Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Murugan (Kumaraswamy)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/11.jpg', summary: 'One of the most important Murugan temples in Kanchipuram, built by the Pallava kings.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8440, lng: 79.7120, sthalaVaralaru: 'Kumara Kottam is one of the most important Murugan temples in Kanchipuram, believed to have been built during the Pallava period. The name means "Fortress of the Prince (Kumara)." Lord Murugan here is worshipped with his consorts Valli and Devasena. The temple is believed to be where Murugan rested after his cosmic battle with the demons. It was one of the principal temples of the Pallava capital and has inscriptions documenting its royal patronage. The annual Skanda Sashti and Thaipusam festivals draw large crowds.' },
    { id: 'knc12', name: 'Chitragupta Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Chitragupta (Keeper of Records)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/12.jpg', summary: 'Extremely rare temple dedicated to Chitragupta, the divine accountant who records all deeds.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8470, lng: 79.7040, sthalaVaralaru: 'Chitragupta Temple in Kanchipuram is one of the extremely rare temples in India dedicated to Chitragupta — the divine scribe who maintains the record of every person\'s good and bad deeds. After death, Chitragupta reads out the balance sheet of one\'s actions before Yama (God of Death), determining the soul\'s fate. Only a handful of Chitragupta temples exist in all of India. The Kayastha community considers Chitragupta their patron deity. The temple emphasizes karma and the importance of righteous living. Devotees pray here for their past sins to be absolved.' },
    { id: 'knc13', name: 'Iravathaneswarar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Iravathaneswarar)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/13.jpg', summary: 'Pallava-era cave temple with exquisite rock-cut sculptures of Shiva and deities.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8480, lng: 79.7000, sthalaVaralaru: 'Iravathaneswarar Temple is a Pallava-era rock-cut cave temple with some of the finest early Dravidian sculptural art. Airavata (Indra\'s divine elephant) worshipped Shiva here, hence the name. The temple features exquisite rock-cut reliefs depicting Shiva in various forms — Nataraja, Dakshinamurthy, Lingodbhava, and Ardhanareeswara. The Pallava sculptors demonstrated their mastery of stone carving here. The temple is smaller but artistically one of the most significant in Kanchipuram, showing the evolution from rock-cut to structural temple architecture.' },
    { id: 'knc14', name: 'Muktheeswarar Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Muktheeswarar)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/14.jpg', summary: 'Temple of salvation — where Shiva grants moksha (liberation) to sincere devotees.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8460, lng: 79.7060, sthalaVaralaru: 'Muktheeswarar Temple is where Lord Shiva is worshipped as the granter of Mukthi (salvation/liberation). Devotees believe that sincere worship here helps attain moksha — freedom from the cycle of birth and death. The temple is part of the Shiva Kanchi division of the city. It was patronized by the Chola and Vijayanagara kings. The temple has beautiful stone carvings and a serene ambiance. Many devotees visit in their final years seeking the Lord\'s grace for liberation.' },
    { id: 'knc15', name: 'Onnakanthan Thali Temple', location: 'Kanchipuram', district: 'Kanchipuram', deity: 'Lord Shiva (Onnakanthan)', image: 'images/kanchipuram/15.jpg', summary: 'Ancient temple mentioned in Sangam literature; where Shiva performed penance for the world\'s welfare.', timings: 'Morning: 6:00 AM - 12:00 PM | Evening: 4:00 PM - 8:00 PM', lat: 12.8500, lng: 79.7080, sthalaVaralaru: 'Onnakanthan Thali is one of the most ancient Shiva temples in Kanchipuram, with references in Sangam-era Tamil literature dating back over 2,000 years. Onnakanthan refers to the "peerless Lord" — Shiva who has no equal. The word Thali refers to a sacred precinct. The temple predates the Pallava period and was later expanded by successive dynasties. Its mention in Sangam literature makes it one of the historically documented temples of ancient Tamil Nadu. The temple has a simple but deeply spiritual ambiance reflecting its ancient origins.' }
  ]
};

